9118  NULL - a contiguous range could not be found to satisfy the request.
9119 
9120  NON-NULL - Returns a pointer (virtual address in the nonpaged portion
9121  of the system) to the allocated physically contiguous
9122  memory.
9123 
9124 Environment:
9125 
9126  Kernel mode, IRQL of DISPATCH_LEVEL or below.
9127 
9128 --*/
9129 
9130 {
9131  PVOID BaseAddress;
9132  PFN_NUMBER SizeInPages;
9133  PFN_NUMBER LowestPfn;
9134  PFN_NUMBER HighestPfn;
9135  MI_PFN_CACHE_ATTRIBUTE CacheAttribute;
9136 
9137  ASSERT (NumberOfBytes != 0);
9138 
9139  LowestPfn = LowestAcceptablePfn;
9140 
9141 #if defined (_MI_MORE_THAN_4GB_)
9142  if (MiNoLowMemory != 0) {
9143  if (HighestAcceptablePfn < MiNoLowMemory) {
9144 
9145  return MiAllocateLowMemory (NumberOfBytes,
9146  LowestAcceptablePfn,
9147  HighestAcceptablePfn,
9148  BoundaryPfn,
9149  CallingAddress,
9150  CacheType,
9151  'tnoC');
9152  }
9153  LowestPfn = MiNoLowMemory;
9154  }
9155 #endif
9156 
9157  CacheAttribute = MI_TRANSLATE_CACHETYPE (CacheType, 0);
9158 
9159  //
9160  // N.B. This setting of SizeInPages to exactly the request size
9161  // means the non-NULL return value from MiCheckForContiguousMemory
9162  // is guaranteed to be the BaseAddress. If this size is ever
9163  // changed, then the non-NULL return value must be checked and
9164  // split/returned accordingly.
9165  //
9166 
9167  SizeInPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES (NumberOfBytes);
9168  HighestPfn = HighestAcceptablePfn;
9169 
9170  if (CacheAttribute == MiCached) {
9171 
9172  BaseAddress = ExAllocatePoolWithTag (NonPagedPoolCacheAligned,
9173  NumberOfBytes,
9174  'mCmM');
9175 
9176  if (BaseAddress != NULL) {
9177 
9178  if (MiCheckForContiguousMemory (BaseAddress,
9179  SizeInPages,
9180  SizeInPages,
9181  LowestPfn,
9182  HighestPfn,
9183  BoundaryPfn,
9184  CacheAttribute)) {
9185 
9186  return BaseAddress;
9187  }
9188 
9189  //
9190  // The allocation from pool does not meet the contiguous
9191  // requirements. Free the allocation and see if any of
9192  // the free pool pages do.
9193  //
9194 
9195  ExFreePool (BaseAddress);
9196  }
9197  }
9198 
9199  if (KeGetCurrentIrql() > APC_LEVEL) {
9200  return NULL;
9201  }
9202 
9203  BaseAddress = MiFindContiguousMemory (LowestPfn,
9204  HighestPfn,
9205  BoundaryPfn,
9206  SizeInPages,
9207  CacheType,
9208  CallingAddress);
9209 
9210  return BaseAddress;
9211 }
9212 
9213 
9214 __bcount(NumberOfBytes) PVOID
9215 MmAllocateContiguousMemorySpecifyCache (
9216  __in SIZE_T NumberOfBytes,
9217  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS LowestAcceptableAddress,
9218  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS HighestAcceptableAddress,
9219  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS BoundaryAddressMultiple,
9220  __in MEMORY_CACHING_TYPE CacheType
9221  )
9222 
9223 /*++
9224 
9225 Routine Description:
9226 
9227  This function allocates a range of physically contiguous non-cached,
9228  non-paged memory. This is accomplished by using MmAllocateContiguousMemory
9229  which uses nonpaged pool virtual addresses to map the found memory chunk.
9230 
9231  Then this function establishes another map to the same physical addresses,
9232  but this alternate map is initialized as non-cached. All references by
9233  our caller will be done through this alternate map.
9234 
9235  This routine is designed to be used by a driver's initialization
9236  routine to allocate a contiguous block of noncached physical memory for
9237  things like the AGP GART.
9238 
9239 Arguments:
9240 
9241  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to allocate.
9242 
9243  LowestAcceptableAddress - Supplies the lowest physical address
9244  which is valid for the allocation. For
9245  example, if the device can only reference
9246  physical memory in the 8M to 16MB range, this
9247  value would be set to 0x800000 (8Mb).
9248 
9249  HighestAcceptableAddress - Supplies the highest physical address
9250  which is valid for the allocation. For
9251  example, if the device can only reference
9252  physical memory below 16MB, this
9253  value would be set to 0xFFFFFF (16Mb - 1).
9254 
9255  BoundaryAddressMultiple - Supplies the physical address multiple this
9256  allocation must not cross.
9257 
9258 Return Value:
9259 
9260  NULL - a contiguous range could not be found to satisfy the request.
9261 
9262  NON-NULL - Returns a pointer (virtual address in the nonpaged portion
9263  of the system) to the allocated physically contiguous
9264  memory.
9265 
9266 Environment:
9267 
9268  Kernel mode, IRQL of DISPATCH_LEVEL or below.
9269 
9270 --*/
9271 
9272 {
9273  PVOID BaseAddress;
9274  PFN_NUMBER LowestPfn;
9275  PFN_NUMBER HighestPfn;
9276  PFN_NUMBER BoundaryPfn;
9277  PVOID CallingAddress;
9278  PVOID CallersCaller;
9279 
9280  RtlGetCallersAddress (&CallingAddress, &CallersCaller);
9281 
9282  ASSERT (NumberOfBytes != 0);
9283 
9284  LowestPfn = (PFN_NUMBER)(LowestAcceptableAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
9285  if (BYTE_OFFSET(LowestAcceptableAddress.LowPart)) {
9286  LowestPfn += 1;
9287  }
9288 
9289  if (BYTE_OFFSET(BoundaryAddressMultiple.LowPart)) {
9290  return NULL;
9291  }
9292 
9293  BoundaryPfn = (PFN_NUMBER)(BoundaryAddressMultiple.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
9294 
9295  HighestPfn = (PFN_NUMBER)(HighestAcceptableAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
9296 
9297  if (HighestPfn > MmHighestPossiblePhysicalPage) {
9298  HighestPfn = MmHighestPossiblePhysicalPage;
9299  }
9300 
9301  if (LowestPfn > HighestPfn) {
9302 
9303  //
9304  // The caller's range is beyond what physically exists, it cannot
9305  // succeed. Bail now to avoid an expensive fruitless search.
9306  //
9307 
9308  return NULL;
9309  }
9310 
9311  BaseAddress = MiAllocateContiguousMemory (NumberOfBytes,
9312  LowestPfn,
9313  HighestPfn,
9314  BoundaryPfn,
9315  CacheType,
9316  CallingAddress);
9317 
9318  return BaseAddress;
9319 }
9320 
9321 __bcount(NumberOfBytes) PVOID
9322 MmAllocateContiguousMemory (
9323  __in SIZE_T NumberOfBytes,
9324  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS HighestAcceptableAddress
9325  )
9326 
9327 /*++
9328 
9329 Routine Description:
9330 
9331  This function allocates a range of physically contiguous non-paged pool.
9332 
9333  This routine is designed to be used by a driver's initialization
9334  routine to allocate a contiguous block of physical memory for
9335  issuing DMA requests from.
9336 
9337 Arguments:
9338 
9339  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to allocate.
9340 
9341  HighestAcceptableAddress - Supplies the highest physical address
9342  which is valid for the allocation. For
9343  example, if the device can only reference
9344  physical memory in the lower 16MB this
9345  value would be set to 0xFFFFFF (16Mb - 1).
9346 
9347 Return Value:
9348 
9349  NULL - a contiguous range could not be found to satisfy the request.
9350 
9351  NON-NULL - Returns a pointer (virtual address in the nonpaged portion
9352  of the system) to the allocated physically contiguous
9353  memory.
9354 
9355 Environment:
9356 
9357  Kernel mode, IRQL of DISPATCH_LEVEL or below.
9358 
9359 --*/
9360 
9361 {
9362  PFN_NUMBER HighestPfn;
9363  PVOID CallingAddress;
9364  PVOID VirtualAddress;
9365  PVOID CallersCaller;
9366 
9367  RtlGetCallersAddress (&CallingAddress, &CallersCaller);
9368 
9369  HighestPfn = (PFN_NUMBER)(HighestAcceptableAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
9370 
9371  if (HighestPfn > MmHighestPossiblePhysicalPage) {
9372  HighestPfn = MmHighestPossiblePhysicalPage;
9373  }
9374 
9375  VirtualAddress = MiAllocateContiguousMemory (NumberOfBytes,
9376  0,
9377  HighestPfn,
9378  0,
9379  MmCached,
9380  CallingAddress);
9381 
9382  return VirtualAddress;
9383 }
9384 
9385 #if defined (_WIN64)
9386 #define SPECIAL_POOL_ADDRESS(p) \
9387  ((((p) >= MmSpecialPoolStart) && ((p) < MmSpecialPoolEnd)) || \
9388  (((p) >= MmSessionSpecialPoolStart) && ((p) < MmSessionSpecialPoolEnd)))
9389 #else
9390 #define SPECIAL_POOL_ADDRESS(p) \
9391  (((p) >= MmSpecialPoolStart) && ((p) < MmSpecialPoolEnd))
9392 #endif

9394 
9395 VOID
9396 MmFreeContiguousMemory (
9397  __in PVOID BaseAddress
9398  )
9399 
9400 /*++
9401 
9402 Routine Description:
9403 
9404  This function deallocates a range of physically contiguous non-paged
9405  pool which was allocated with the MmAllocateContiguousMemory function.
9406 
9407 Arguments:
9408 
9409  BaseAddress - Supplies the base virtual address where the physical
9410  address was previously mapped.
9411 
9412 Return Value:
9413 
9414  None.
9415 
9416 Environment:
9417 
9418  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
9419 
9420 --*/
9421 
9422 {
9423  KIRQL OldIrql;
9424  ULONG SizeInPages;
9425  PMMPTE PointerPte;
9426  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
9427  PFN_NUMBER LastPage;
9428  PMMPFN Pfn1;
9429  PMMPFN StartPfn;
9430 
9431  PAGED_CODE();
9432 
9433 #if defined (_MI_MORE_THAN_4GB_)
9434  if (MiNoLowMemory != 0) {
9435  if (MiFreeLowMemory (BaseAddress, 'tnoC') == TRUE) {
9436  return;
9437  }
9438  }
9439 #endif
9440 
9441  if (((BaseAddress >= MmNonPagedPoolStart) &&
9442  (BaseAddress < (PVOID)((ULONG_PTR)MmNonPagedPoolStart + MmSizeOfNonPagedPoolInBytes))) ||
9443 
9444  ((BaseAddress >= MmNonPagedPoolExpansionStart) &&
9445  (BaseAddress < MmNonPagedPoolEnd)) ||
9446 
9447  (SPECIAL_POOL_ADDRESS(BaseAddress))) {
9448 
9449  ExFreePool (BaseAddress);
9450  }
9451  else {
9452 
9453  //
9454  // The contiguous memory being freed may be the target of a delayed
9455  // unlock. Since these pages may be immediately released, force
9456  // any pending delayed actions to occur now.
9457  //
9458 
9459  MiDeferredUnlockPages (0);
9460 
9461  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (BaseAddress);
9462  PageFrameIndex = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (PointerPte);
9463  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
9464 
9465  if (Pfn1->u3.e1.StartOfAllocation == 0) {
9466  KeBugCheckEx (BAD_POOL_CALLER,
9467  0x60,
9468  (ULONG_PTR)BaseAddress,
9469  0,
9470  0);
9471  }
9472 
9473  StartPfn = Pfn1;
9474  Pfn1->u3.e1.StartOfAllocation = 0;
9475  Pfn1 -= 1;
9476 
9477  do {
9478  Pfn1 += 1;
9479  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount == 1);
9480  ASSERT (Pfn1->u2.ShareCount == 1);
9481  ASSERT (Pfn1->PteAddress == PointerPte);
9482  ASSERT (Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long == MM_DEMAND_ZERO_WRITE_PTE);
9483  ASSERT (Pfn1->u4.PteFrame == MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (MiGetPteAddress(PointerPte)));
9484  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e1.PageLocation == ActiveAndValid);
9485  ASSERT (Pfn1->u4.VerifierAllocation == 0);
9486  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e1.LargeSessionAllocation == 0);
9487  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e1.PrototypePte == 0);
9488  MI_SET_PFN_DELETED(Pfn1);
9489  PointerPte += 1;
9490 
9491  } while (Pfn1->u3.e1.EndOfAllocation == 0);
9492 
9493  Pfn1->u3.e1.EndOfAllocation = 0;
9494 
9495  SizeInPages = (ULONG)(Pfn1 - StartPfn + 1);
9496 
9497  //
9498  // Notify deadlock verifier that a region that can contain locks
9499  // will become invalid.
9500  //
9501 
9502  if (MmVerifierData.Level & DRIVER_VERIFIER_DEADLOCK_DETECTION) {
9503  VerifierDeadlockFreePool (BaseAddress, SizeInPages << PAGE_SHIFT);
9504  }
9505 
9506  //
9507  // Release the mapping.
9508  //
9509 
9510  MmUnmapIoSpace (BaseAddress, SizeInPages << PAGE_SHIFT);
9511 
9512  //
9513  // Release the actual pages.
9514  //
9515 
9516  LastPage = PageFrameIndex + SizeInPages;
9517 
9518  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
9519 
9520  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9521 
9522  do {
9523  MiDecrementShareCount (Pfn1, PageFrameIndex);
9524  PageFrameIndex += 1;
9525  Pfn1 += 1;
9526  } while (PageFrameIndex < LastPage);
9527 
9528  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9529 
9530  MI_INCREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (SizeInPages, MM_RESAVAIL_FREE_CONTIGUOUS2);
9531 
9532  MiReturnCommitment (SizeInPages);
9533  }
9534 }

9580 
9581 PVOID
9582 MmAllocateIndependentPages (
9583  IN SIZE_T NumberOfBytes,
9584  IN ULONG Node
9585  )
9586 
9587 /*++
9588 
9589 Routine Description:
9590 
9591  This function allocates a range of virtually contiguous nonpaged pages
9592  without using superpages. This allows the caller to apply independent
9593  page protections to each page.
9594 
9595 Arguments:
9596 
9597  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to allocate.
9598 
9599  Node - Supplies the preferred node number for the backing physical pages.
9600  If pages on the preferred node are not available, any page will
9601  be used. -1 indicates no preferred node.
9602 
9603 Return Value:
9604 
9605  The virtual address of the memory or NULL if none could be allocated.
9606 
9607 Environment:
9608 
9609  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
9610 
9611 --*/
9612 
9613 {
9614  ULONG PageColor;
9615  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages;
9616  PMMPTE PointerPte;
9617  MMPTE TempPte;
9618  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
9619  PVOID BaseAddress;
9620  KIRQL OldIrql;
9621 
9622  ASSERT ((Node == (ULONG)-1) || (Node < KeNumberNodes));
9623 
9624  NumberOfPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES (NumberOfBytes);
9625 
9626  PointerPte = MiReserveSystemPtes ((ULONG)NumberOfPages, SystemPteSpace);
9627 
9628  if (PointerPte == NULL) {
9629  return NULL;
9630  }
9631 
9632  if (MiChargeCommitment (NumberOfPages, NULL) == FALSE) {
9633  MiReleaseSystemPtes (PointerPte, (ULONG)NumberOfPages, SystemPteSpace);
9634  return NULL;
9635  }
9636 
9637  BaseAddress = (PVOID)MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (PointerPte);
9638 
9639  MI_MAKE_VALID_KERNEL_PTE (TempPte,
9640  0,
9641  MM_READWRITE,
9642  PointerPte);
9643 
9644  MI_SET_PTE_DIRTY (TempPte);
9645 
9646  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9647 
9648  if ((SPFN_NUMBER)NumberOfPages > MI_NONPAGEABLE_MEMORY_AVAILABLE()) {
9649  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9650  MiReturnCommitment (NumberOfPages);
9651  MiReleaseSystemPtes (PointerPte, (ULONG)NumberOfPages, SystemPteSpace);
9652  return NULL;
9653  }
9654 
9655  MM_TRACK_COMMIT (MM_DBG_COMMIT_INDEPENDENT_PAGES, NumberOfPages);
9656 
9657  MI_DECREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (NumberOfPages, MM_RESAVAIL_ALLOCATE_INDEPENDENT);
9658 
9659  do {
9660  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 0);
9661 
9662  if (MmAvailablePages < MM_HIGH_LIMIT) {
9663  MiEnsureAvailablePageOrWait (NULL, OldIrql);
9664  }
9665 
9666  if (Node == (ULONG)-1) {
9667  PageColor = MI_GET_PAGE_COLOR_FROM_PTE (PointerPte);
9668  }
9669  else {
9670  PageColor = (((MI_SYSTEM_PAGE_COLOR++) & MmSecondaryColorMask) |
9671  (Node << MmSecondaryColorNodeShift));
9672  }
9673 
9674  PageFrameIndex = MiRemoveAnyPage (PageColor);
9675 
9676  TempPte.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber = PageFrameIndex;
9677 
9678  MiInitializePfnAndMakePteValid (PageFrameIndex, PointerPte, TempPte);
9679 
9680  PointerPte += 1;
9681  NumberOfPages -= 1;
9682  } while (NumberOfPages != 0);
9683 
9684  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9685 
9686  NumberOfPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES (NumberOfBytes);
9687 
9688  return BaseAddress;
9689 }
9690 
9691 BOOLEAN
9692 MmSetPageProtection (
9693  __in_bcount(NumberOfBytes) PVOID VirtualAddress,
9694  __in SIZE_T NumberOfBytes,
9695  __in ULONG NewProtect
9696  )
9697 
9698 /*++
9699 
9700 Routine Description:
9701 
9702  This function sets the specified virtual address range to the desired
9703  protection. This assumes that the virtual addresses are backed by PTEs
9704  which can be set (ie: not in kseg0 or large pages).
9705 
9706 Arguments:
9707 
9708  VirtualAddress - Supplies the start address to protect.
9709 
9710  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to set.
9711 
9712  NewProtect - Supplies the protection to set the pages to (PAGE_XX).
9713 
9714 Return Value:
9715 
9716  TRUE if the protection was applied, FALSE if not.
9717 
9718 Environment:
9719 
9720  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
9721 
9722 --*/
9723 
9724 {
9725  PFN_NUMBER i;
9726  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages;
9727  PMMPTE PointerPte;
9728  MMPTE TempPte;
9729  MMPTE NewPteContents;
9730  KIRQL OldIrql;
9731  ULONG ProtectionMask;
9732  PVOID VaFlushList[MM_MAXIMUM_FLUSH_COUNT];
9733 
9734  ASSERT (KeGetCurrentIrql() <= APC_LEVEL);
9735 
9736  if (MI_IS_PHYSICAL_ADDRESS (VirtualAddress)) {
9737  return FALSE;
9738  }
9739 
9740  ProtectionMask = MiMakeProtectionMask (NewProtect);
9741  if (ProtectionMask == MM_INVALID_PROTECTION) {
9742  return FALSE;
9743  }
9744 
9745  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (VirtualAddress);
9746  NumberOfPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES (NumberOfBytes);
9747  ASSERT (NumberOfPages != 0);
9748 
9749  MI_MAKE_VALID_KERNEL_PTE (NewPteContents,
9750  0,
9751  ProtectionMask,
9752  PointerPte);
9753 
9754  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9755 
9756  for (i = 0; i < NumberOfPages; i += 1) {
9757 
9758  TempPte = *PointerPte;
9759 
9760  NewPteContents.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber = TempPte.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber;
9761  NewPteContents.u.Hard.Dirty = TempPte.u.Hard.Dirty;
9762 
9763  MI_WRITE_VALID_PTE_NEW_PROTECTION (PointerPte, NewPteContents);
9764 
9765  PointerPte += 1;
9766  }
9767 
9768  if (NumberOfPages == 1) {
9769  MI_FLUSH_SINGLE_TB (VirtualAddress, TRUE);
9770  }
9771  else if (NumberOfPages < MM_MAXIMUM_FLUSH_COUNT) {
9772 
9773  for (i = 0; i < NumberOfPages; i += 1) {
9774  VaFlushList[i] = (PVOID)((PUCHAR)VirtualAddress + (i << PAGE_SHIFT));
9775  }
9776  MI_FLUSH_MULTIPLE_TB ((ULONG)NumberOfPages, &VaFlushList[0], TRUE);
9777  }
9778  else {
9779  MI_FLUSH_ENTIRE_TB (0x13);
9780  }
9781 
9782  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9783 
9784  return TRUE;
9785 }
9786 
9787 VOID
9788 MmFreeIndependentPages (
9789  IN PVOID VirtualAddress,
9790  IN SIZE_T NumberOfBytes
9791  )
9792 
9793 /*++
9794 
9795 Routine Description:
9796 
9797  Returns pages previously allocated with MmAllocateIndependentPages.
9798 
9799 Arguments:
9800 
9801  VirtualAddress - Supplies the virtual address to free.
9802 
9803  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to free.
9804 
9805 Return Value:
9806 
9807  None.
9808 
9809 Environment:
9810 
9811  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
9812 
9813 --*/
9814 
9815 {
9816  KIRQL OldIrql;
9817  MMPTE PteContents;
9818  PMMPTE PointerPte;
9819  PMMPTE BasePte;
9820  PMMPTE EndPte;
9821  PMMPFN Pfn1;
9822  PMMPFN Pfn2;
9823  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages;
9824  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
9825 
9826  ASSERT (KeGetCurrentIrql() <= APC_LEVEL);
9827 
9828  NumberOfPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES (NumberOfBytes);
9829 
9830  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (VirtualAddress);
9831  BasePte = PointerPte;
9832  EndPte = PointerPte + NumberOfPages;
9833 
9834  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9835 
9836  do {
9837 
9838  PteContents = *PointerPte;
9839 
9840  ASSERT (PteContents.u.Hard.Valid == 1);
9841 
9842  PageFrameIndex = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (&PteContents);
9843 
9844  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
9845  Pfn2 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (Pfn1->u4.PteFrame);
9846 
9847  MiDecrementShareCount (Pfn2, Pfn1->u4.PteFrame);
9848 
9849  MI_SET_PFN_DELETED (Pfn1);
9850  MiDecrementShareCount (Pfn1, PageFrameIndex);
9851 
9852  PointerPte += 1;
9853 
9854  } while (PointerPte < EndPte);
9855 
9856  //
9857  // Update the count of resident available pages.
9858  //
9859 
9860  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
9861 
9862  MI_INCREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (NumberOfPages, MM_RESAVAIL_FREE_INDEPENDENT);
9863 
9864  //
9865  // Return PTEs and commitment.
9866  //
9867 
9868  MiReleaseSystemPtes (BasePte, (ULONG)NumberOfPages, SystemPteSpace);
9869 
9870  MiReturnCommitment (NumberOfPages);
9871 
9872  MM_TRACK_COMMIT (MM_DBG_COMMIT_INDEPENDENT_PAGES, NumberOfPages);
9873 }
9874 
9875 
9876 VOID
9877 MiZeroAwePageWorker (
9878  IN PVOID Context
9879  )
9880 
9881 /*++
9882 
9883 Routine Description:
9884 
9885  This routine is the worker routine executed by all processors to
9886  fan out page zeroing for AWE allocations.
9887 
9888 Arguments:
9889 
9890  Context - Supplies a pointer to the workitem.
9891 
9892 Return Value:
9893 
9894  None.
9895 
9896 Environment:
9897 
9898  Kernel mode.
9899 
9900 --*/
9901 
9902 {
9903 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
9904  LOGICAL SetIdeal;
9905  ULONG Processor;
9906  PEPROCESS DefaultProcess;
9907 #endif
9908  PKTHREAD Thread;
9909  KPRIORITY OldPriority;
9910  PMMPFN Pfn1;
9911  SCHAR OldBasePriority;
9912  PMMPFN PfnNextColored;
9913  PCOLORED_PAGE_INFO ColoredPageInfo;
9914  MMPTE TempPte;
9915  MMPTE TempCachedPte;
9916  PMMPTE BasePte;
9917  PMMPTE PointerPte;
9918  PVOID VirtualAddress;
9919  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
9920  PFN_COUNT i;
9921  PFN_COUNT RequestedPtes;
9922 
9923  ColoredPageInfo = (PCOLORED_PAGE_INFO) Context;
9924 
9925  //
9926  // Use the initiating thread's priority instead of the default system
9927  // thread priority.
9928  //
9929 
9930  Thread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
9931  OldBasePriority = Thread->BasePriority;
9932  Thread->BasePriority = ColoredPageInfo->BasePriority;
9933  OldPriority = KeSetPriorityThread (Thread, Thread->BasePriority);
9934 
9935  //
9936  // Dispatch each worker thread to a processor local to the memory being
9937  // zeroed.
9938  //
9939 
9940 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
9941  Processor = 0;
9942 
9943  if (PsInitialSystemProcess != NULL) {
9944  DefaultProcess = PsInitialSystemProcess;
9945  }
9946  else {
9947  DefaultProcess = PsIdleProcess;
9948  }
9949 
9950  if ((ColoredPageInfo->Affinity != 0) &&
9951  (ColoredPageInfo->Affinity != DefaultProcess->Pcb.Affinity)) {
9952 
9953  KeFindFirstSetLeftAffinity (ColoredPageInfo->Affinity, &Processor);
9954 
9955  //
9956  // Only affinitize if the node has a processor.
9957  //
9958 
9959  if (Processor != NO_BITS_FOUND) {
9960  Processor = (CCHAR) KeSetIdealProcessorThread (Thread,
9961  (CCHAR) Processor);
9962  SetIdeal = TRUE;
9963  }
9964  else {
9965  SetIdeal = FALSE;
9966  }
9967  }
9968  else {
9969  SetIdeal = FALSE;
9970  }
9971 #endif
9972 
9973  Pfn1 = ColoredPageInfo->PfnAllocation;
9974 
9975  ASSERT (Pfn1 != (PMMPFN) MM_EMPTY_LIST);
9976  ASSERT (ColoredPageInfo->PagesQueued != 0);
9977 
9978  //
9979  // Zero all argument pages.
9980  //
9981 
9982  do {
9983 
9984  ASSERT (ColoredPageInfo->PagesQueued != 0);
9985 
9986  RequestedPtes = ColoredPageInfo->PagesQueued;
9987 
9988 #if !defined (_WIN64)
9989 
9990  //
9991  // NT64 has an abundance of PTEs so try to map the whole request with
9992  // a single call. For NT32, this resource needs to be carefully shared.
9993  //
9994 
9995  if (RequestedPtes > (1024 * 1024) / PAGE_SIZE) {
9996  RequestedPtes = (1024 * 1024) / PAGE_SIZE;
9997  }
9998 #endif
9999 
10000  do {
10001  BasePte = MiReserveSystemPtes (RequestedPtes, SystemPteSpace);
10002 
10003  if (BasePte != NULL) {
10004  break;
10005  }
10006 
10007  RequestedPtes >>= 1;
10008 
10009  } while (RequestedPtes != 0);
10010 
10011  if (BasePte != NULL) {
10012 
10013  //
10014  // Able to get a reasonable chunk, go for a big zero.
10015  //
10016 
10017  PointerPte = BasePte;
10018 
10019  MI_MAKE_VALID_KERNEL_PTE (TempCachedPte,
10020  0,
10021  MM_READWRITE,
10022  PointerPte);
10023 
10024  MI_SET_PTE_DIRTY (TempCachedPte);
10025 
10026  for (i = 0; i < RequestedPtes; i += 1) {
10027 
10028  ASSERT (Pfn1 != (PMMPFN) MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10029 
10030  PageFrameIndex = MI_PFN_ELEMENT_TO_INDEX (Pfn1);
10031 
10032  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 0);
10033 
10034  TempPte = TempCachedPte;
10035 
10036  switch (Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute) {
10037  case MiCached:
10038  break;
10039 
10040  case MiNonCached:
10041  MI_DISABLE_CACHING (TempPte);
10042  break;
10043 
10044  case MiWriteCombined:
10045  MI_SET_PTE_WRITE_COMBINE (TempPte);
10046  break;
10047 
10048  default:
10049  break;
10050  }
10051 
10052  TempPte.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber = PageFrameIndex;
10053 
10054  MI_WRITE_VALID_PTE (PointerPte, TempPte);
10055 
10056  PfnNextColored = (PMMPFN) (ULONG_PTR) Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long;
10057  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = MM_DEMAND_ZERO_WRITE_PTE;
10058  Pfn1 = PfnNextColored;
10059 
10060  PointerPte += 1;
10061  }
10062 
10063  ColoredPageInfo->PagesQueued -= RequestedPtes;
10064 
10065  VirtualAddress = MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (BasePte);
10066 
10067  KeZeroPages (VirtualAddress, ((ULONG_PTR)RequestedPtes) << PAGE_SHIFT);
10068 
10069  MiReleaseSystemPtes (BasePte, RequestedPtes, SystemPteSpace);
10070  }
10071  else {
10072 
10073  //
10074  // No PTEs left, zero a single page at a time.
10075  //
10076 
10077  MiZeroPhysicalPage (MI_PFN_ELEMENT_TO_INDEX (Pfn1));
10078 
10079  PfnNextColored = (PMMPFN) (ULONG_PTR) Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long;
10080  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = MM_DEMAND_ZERO_WRITE_PTE;
10081  Pfn1 = PfnNextColored;
10082 
10083  ColoredPageInfo->PagesQueued -= 1;
10084  }
10085 
10086  } while (Pfn1 != (PMMPFN) MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10087 
10088  //
10089  // Let the initiator know we've zeroed our share.
10090  //
10091 
10092  KeSetEvent (&ColoredPageInfo->Event, 0, FALSE);
10093 
10094  //
10095  // Restore the entry thread priority and ideal processor - this is critical
10096  // if we were called directly from the initiator instead of in the
10097  // context of a system thread.
10098  //
10099 
10100 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
10101  if (SetIdeal == TRUE) {
10102  KeSetIdealProcessorThread (Thread, (CCHAR) Processor);
10103  }
10104 #endif
10105 
10106  KeSetPriorityThread (Thread, OldPriority);
10107  Thread->BasePriority = OldBasePriority;
10108 
10109  return;
10110 }
10111 
10112 VOID
10113 MiZeroInParallel (
10114  IN PCOLORED_PAGE_INFO ColoredPageInfoBase
10115  )
10116 
10117 /*++
10118 
10119 Routine Description:
10120 
10121  This routine zeroes all the free & standby pages, fanning out the work.
10122  This is done even on UP machines because the worker thread code maps
10123  large MDLs and is thus better performing than zeroing a single
10124  page at a time.
10125 
10126 Arguments:
10127 
10128  ColoredPageInfoBase - Supplies the informational structure about which
10129  pages to zero.
10130 
10131 Return Value:
10132 
10133  None.
10134 
10135 Environment:
10136 
10137  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below. The caller must lock down the
10138  PAGELK section that this routine resides in.
10139 
10140 --*/
10141 
10142 {
10143 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
10144  ULONG i;
10145 #endif
10146  ULONG WaitCount;
10147  PKEVENT WaitObjects[MAXIMUM_WAIT_OBJECTS];
10148  KWAIT_BLOCK WaitBlockArray[MAXIMUM_WAIT_OBJECTS];
10149  KPRIORITY OldPriority;
10150  SCHAR OldBasePriority;
10151  NTSTATUS WakeupStatus;
10152  PETHREAD EThread;
10153  PKTHREAD Thread;
10154  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES ObjectAttributes;
10155  HANDLE ThreadHandle;
10156  SCHAR WorkerThreadPriority;
10157  PCOLORED_PAGE_INFO ColoredPageInfo;
10158  ULONG Color;
10159  PMMPFN Pfn1;
10160  NTSTATUS Status;
10161 
10162  WaitCount = 0;
10163 
10164  EThread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
10165  Thread = &EThread->Tcb;
10166 
10167  //
10168  // Raise our priority to the highest non-realtime priority. This
10169  // usually allows us to spawn all our worker threads without
10170  // interruption from them, but also doesn't starve the modified or
10171  // mapped page writers because we are going to access pageable code
10172  // and data below and during the spawning.
10173  //
10174 
10175  OldBasePriority = Thread->BasePriority;
10176  ASSERT ((OldBasePriority >= 1) || (InitializationPhase == 0));
10177  Thread->BasePriority = LOW_REALTIME_PRIORITY - 1;
10178  OldPriority = KeSetPriorityThread (Thread, LOW_REALTIME_PRIORITY - 1);
10179  WorkerThreadPriority = OldBasePriority;
10180 
10181  for (Color = 0; Color < MmSecondaryColors; Color += 1) {
10182 
10183  ColoredPageInfo = &ColoredPageInfoBase[Color];
10184 
10185  Pfn1 = ColoredPageInfo->PfnAllocation;
10186 
10187  if (Pfn1 != (PMMPFN) MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
10188 
10189  //
10190  // Assume no memory penalty for non-local memory on this
10191  // machine so there's no need to run with restricted affinity.
10192  //
10193 
10194  ColoredPageInfo->BasePriority = WorkerThreadPriority;
10195 
10196 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
10197 
10198  if (PsInitialSystemProcess != NULL) {
10199  ColoredPageInfo->Affinity = PsInitialSystemProcess->Pcb.Affinity;
10200  }
10201  else {
10202  ColoredPageInfo->Affinity = PsIdleProcess->Pcb.Affinity;
10203  }
10204 
10205  for (i = 0; i < KeNumberNodes; i += 1) {
10206 
10207  if (KeNodeBlock[i]->Color == (Color >> MmSecondaryColorNodeShift)) {
10208  ColoredPageInfo->Affinity = KeNodeBlock[i]->ProcessorMask;
10209  break;
10210  }
10211  }
10212 
10213 #endif
10214 
10215  KeInitializeEvent (&ColoredPageInfo->Event,
10216  SynchronizationEvent,
10217  FALSE);
10218 
10219  //
10220  // Don't spawn threads to zero the memory if we are a system
10221  // thread. This is because this routine can be called by
10222  // drivers in the context of the segment dereference thread, so
10223  // referencing pageable memory here can cause a deadlock.
10224  //
10225 
10226  if ((IS_SYSTEM_THREAD (EThread)) || (InitializationPhase == 0)) {
10227  MiZeroAwePageWorker ((PVOID) ColoredPageInfo);
10228  }
10229  else {
10230 
10231  InitializeObjectAttributes (&ObjectAttributes,
10232  NULL,
10233  0,
10234  NULL,
10235  NULL);
10236 
10237  //
10238  // We are creating a system thread for each memory
10239  // node instead of using the executive worker thread
10240  // pool. This is because we want to run the threads
10241  // at a lower priority to keep the machine responsive
10242  // during all this zeroing. And doing this to a worker
10243  // thread can cause a deadlock as various other
10244  // components (registry, etc) expect worker threads to be
10245  // available at a higher priority right away.
10246  //
10247 
10248  Status = PsCreateSystemThread (&ThreadHandle,
10249  THREAD_ALL_ACCESS,
10250  &ObjectAttributes,
10251  0L,
10252  NULL,
10253  MiZeroAwePageWorker,
10254  (PVOID) ColoredPageInfo);
10255 
10256  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
10257  ZwClose (ThreadHandle);
10258  }
10259  else {
10260  MiZeroAwePageWorker ((PVOID) ColoredPageInfo);
10261  }
10262  }
10263 
10264  WaitObjects[WaitCount] = &ColoredPageInfo->Event;
10265 
10266  WaitCount += 1;
10267 
10268  if (WaitCount == MAXIMUM_WAIT_OBJECTS) {
10269 
10270  //
10271  // Done issuing the first round of workitems,
10272  // lower priority & wait.
10273  //
10274 
10275  KeSetPriorityThread (Thread, OldPriority);
10276  Thread->BasePriority = OldBasePriority;
10277 
10278  WakeupStatus = KeWaitForMultipleObjects (WaitCount,
10279  &WaitObjects[0],
10280  WaitAll,
10281  Executive,
10282  KernelMode,
10283  FALSE,
10284  NULL,
10285  &WaitBlockArray[0]);
10286  ASSERT (WakeupStatus == STATUS_SUCCESS);
10287 
10288  WaitCount = 0;
10289 
10290  Thread->BasePriority = LOW_REALTIME_PRIORITY - 1;
10291  KeSetPriorityThread (Thread, LOW_REALTIME_PRIORITY - 1);
10292  }
10293  }
10294  }
10295 
10296  //
10297  // Done issuing all the workitems, lower priority & wait.
10298  //
10299 
10300  KeSetPriorityThread (Thread, OldPriority);
10301  Thread->BasePriority = OldBasePriority;
10302 
10303  if (WaitCount != 0) {
10304 
10305  WakeupStatus = KeWaitForMultipleObjects (WaitCount,
10306  &WaitObjects[0],
10307  WaitAll,
10308  Executive,
10309  KernelMode,
10310  FALSE,
10311  NULL,
10312  &WaitBlockArray[0]);
10313 
10314  ASSERT (WakeupStatus == STATUS_SUCCESS);
10315  }
10316 
10317  return;
10318 }
10319 
10320 
10321 PMDL
10322 MiAllocatePagesForMdl (
10323  IN PHYSICAL_ADDRESS LowAddress,
10324  IN PHYSICAL_ADDRESS HighAddress,
10325  IN PHYSICAL_ADDRESS SkipBytes,
10326  IN SIZE_T TotalBytes,
10327  IN MI_PFN_CACHE_ATTRIBUTE CacheAttribute,
10328  IN ULONG Flags
10329  )
10330 
10331 /*++
10332 
10333 Routine Description:
10334 
10335  This routine searches the PFN database for free, zeroed or standby pages
10336  to satisfy the request. This does not map the pages - it just allocates
10337  them and puts them into an MDL. It is expected that our caller will
10338  map the MDL as needed.
10339 
10340  NOTE: this routine may return an MDL mapping a smaller number of bytes
10341  than the amount requested. It is the caller's responsibility to check the
10342  MDL upon return for the size actually allocated.
10343 
10344  These pages comprise physical non-paged memory and are zero-filled.
10345 
10346  This routine is designed to be used by an AGP driver to obtain physical
10347  memory in a specified range since hardware may provide substantial
10348  performance wins depending on where the backing memory is allocated.
10349 
10350  Because the caller may use these pages for a noncached mapping, care is
10351  taken to never allocate any pages that reside in a large page (in order
10352  to prevent TB incoherency of the same page being mapped by multiple
10353  translations with different attributes).
10354 
10355 Arguments:
10356 
10357  LowAddress - Supplies the low physical address of the first range that
10358  the allocated pages can come from.
10359 
10360  HighAddress - Supplies the high physical address of the first range that
10361  the allocated pages can come from.
10362 
10363  SkipBytes - Number of bytes to skip (from the Low Address) to get to the
10364  next physical address range that allocated pages can come from.
10365 
10366  TotalBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to allocate.
10367 
10368  Flags - Supplies flags passed by the caller.
10369 
10370 Return Value:
10371 
10372  MDL - An MDL mapping a range of pages in the specified range.
10373  This may map less memory than the caller requested if the full amount
10374  is not currently available.
10375 
10376  NULL - No pages in the specified range OR not enough virtually contiguous
10377  nonpaged pool for the MDL is available at this time.
10378 
10379 Environment:
10380 
10381  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
10382 
10383 --*/
10384 
10385 {
10386  PKPRCB Prcb;
10387  PKTHREAD Thread;
10388  ULONG StartColor;
10389  PMDL MemoryDescriptorList;
10390  PMDL MemoryDescriptorList2;
10391  PMMPFN Pfn1;
10392  PMMPFN PfnNextColored;
10393  PMMPFN PfnNextFlink;
10394  PMMPFN PfnLastColored;
10395  KIRQL OldIrql;
10396  PFN_NUMBER start;
10397  PFN_NUMBER Page;
10398  PFN_NUMBER NextPage;
10399  PFN_NUMBER found;
10400  PFN_NUMBER BasePage;
10401  PFN_NUMBER LowPage;
10402  PFN_NUMBER HighPage;
10403  PFN_NUMBER SizeInPages;
10404  PFN_NUMBER MdlPageSpan;
10405  PFN_NUMBER SkipPages;
10406  PFN_NUMBER MaxPages;
10407  PFN_NUMBER PagesExamined;
10408  PPFN_NUMBER MdlPage;
10409  ULONG Color;
10410  PMMCOLOR_TABLES ColorHead;
10411  MMLISTS MemoryList;
10412  PFN_NUMBER LowPage1;
10413  PFN_NUMBER HighPage1;
10414  LOGICAL PagePlacementOk;
10415  PFN_NUMBER PageNextColored;
10416  PFN_NUMBER PageNextFlink;
10417  PFN_NUMBER PageLastColored;
10418  PMMPFNLIST ListHead;
10419  PCOLORED_PAGE_INFO ColoredPageInfoBase;
10420  PCOLORED_PAGE_INFO ColoredPageInfo;
10421  ULONG ColorHeadsDrained;
10422  ULONG NodePassesLeft;
10423  ULONG ColorCount;
10424  ULONG BaseColor;
10425  ULONG CacheTypesFound;
10426  PFN_NUMBER ZeroCount;
10427 #if DBG
10428  ULONG i;
10429  PPFN_NUMBER LastMdlPage;
10430  ULONG FinishedCount;
10431  PEPROCESS Process;
10432 #endif
10433 
10434  ASSERT (KeGetCurrentIrql() <= APC_LEVEL);
10435 
10436 #if DBG
10437  if (Flags & MI_ALLOCATION_IS_AWE) {
10438  ASSERT ((Flags & ~MI_ALLOCATION_IS_AWE) == 0);
10439  }
10440 #endif
10441 
10442  //
10443  // The skip increment must be a page-size multiple.
10444  //
10445 
10446  if (BYTE_OFFSET(SkipBytes.LowPart)) {
10447  return NULL;
10448  }
10449 
10450  LowPage = (PFN_NUMBER)(LowAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
10451  HighPage = (PFN_NUMBER)(HighAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
10452 
10453  if (HighPage > MmHighestPossiblePhysicalPage) {
10454  HighPage = MmHighestPossiblePhysicalPage;
10455  }
10456 
10457  //
10458  // Maximum allocation size is constrained by the MDL ByteCount field.
10459  //
10460 
10461  if (TotalBytes > (SIZE_T)((ULONG)(MAXULONG - PAGE_SIZE))) {
10462  TotalBytes = (SIZE_T)((ULONG)(MAXULONG - PAGE_SIZE));
10463  }
10464 
10465  SizeInPages = (PFN_NUMBER)ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES(0, TotalBytes);
10466 
10467  SkipPages = (PFN_NUMBER)(SkipBytes.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
10468 
10469  BasePage = LowPage;
10470 
10471  //
10472  // Check without the PFN lock as the actual number of pages to get will
10473  // be recalculated later while holding the lock.
10474  //
10475 
10476  MaxPages = MI_NONPAGEABLE_MEMORY_AVAILABLE() - 1024;
10477 
10478  if ((SPFN_NUMBER)MaxPages <= 0) {
10479  SizeInPages = 0;
10480  }
10481  else if (SizeInPages > MaxPages) {
10482  SizeInPages = MaxPages;
10483  }
10484 
10485  if (SizeInPages == 0) {
10486  return NULL;
10487  }
10488 
10489 #if DBG
10490  if (SizeInPages < (PFN_NUMBER)ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES(0, TotalBytes)) {
10491  if (MiPrintAwe != 0) {
10492  DbgPrintEx (DPFLTR_MM_ID, DPFLTR_INFO_LEVEL,
10493  "MiAllocatePagesForMdl1: unable to get %p pages, trying for %p instead\n",
10494  ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES(0, TotalBytes),
10495  SizeInPages);
10496  }
10497  }
10498 #endif
10499 
10500  //
10501  // Allocate an MDL to return the pages in.
10502  //
10503 
10504  do {
10505  MemoryDescriptorList = MmCreateMdl (NULL,
10506  NULL,
10507  SizeInPages << PAGE_SHIFT);
10508 
10509  if (MemoryDescriptorList != NULL) {
10510  break;
10511  }
10512  SizeInPages -= (SizeInPages >> 4);
10513  } while (SizeInPages != 0);
10514 
10515  if (MemoryDescriptorList == NULL) {
10516  return NULL;
10517  }
10518 
10519  //
10520  // Ensure there is enough commit prior to allocating the pages.
10521  //
10522 
10523  if (MiChargeCommitment (SizeInPages, NULL) == FALSE) {
10524  ExFreePool (MemoryDescriptorList);
10525  return NULL;
10526  }
10527 
10528  //
10529  // Allocate a list of colored anchors.
10530  //
10531 
10532  ColoredPageInfoBase = (PCOLORED_PAGE_INFO) ExAllocatePoolWithTag (
10533  NonPagedPool,
10534  MmSecondaryColors * sizeof (COLORED_PAGE_INFO),
10535  'ldmM');
10536 
10537  if (ColoredPageInfoBase == NULL) {
10538  ExFreePool (MemoryDescriptorList);
10539  MiReturnCommitment (SizeInPages);
10540  return NULL;
10541  }
10542 
10543  for (Color = 0; Color < MmSecondaryColors; Color += 1) {
10544  ColoredPageInfoBase[Color].PfnAllocation = (PMMPFN) MM_EMPTY_LIST;
10545  ColoredPageInfoBase[Color].PagesQueued = 0;
10546  }
10547 
10548  MdlPageSpan = SizeInPages;
10549 
10550  //
10551  // Recalculate the total size while holding the PFN lock.
10552  //
10553 
10554  start = 0;
10555  found = 0;
10556  ZeroCount = 0;
10557  CacheTypesFound = 0;
10558 
10559  MdlPage = (PPFN_NUMBER)(MemoryDescriptorList + 1);
10560 
10561  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle (ExPageLockHandle);
10562 
10563  Thread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
10564 
10565  KeEnterGuardedRegionThread (Thread);
10566  MI_LOCK_DYNAMIC_MEMORY_SHARED ();
10567 
10568  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
10569 
10570  MiDeferredUnlockPages (MI_DEFER_PFN_HELD);
10571 
10572  MaxPages = MI_NONPAGEABLE_MEMORY_AVAILABLE() - 1024;
10573 
10574  if ((SPFN_NUMBER)MaxPages <= 0) {
10575  SizeInPages = 0;
10576  }
10577  else if (SizeInPages > MaxPages) {
10578  SizeInPages = MaxPages;
10579  }
10580 
10581  //
10582  // Systems utilizing memory compression may have more pages on the zero,
10583  // free and standby lists than we want to give out. Explicitly check
10584  // MmAvailablePages instead (and recheck whenever the PFN lock is released
10585  // and reacquired).
10586  //
10587 
10588  if ((SPFN_NUMBER)SizeInPages > (SPFN_NUMBER)(MmAvailablePages - MM_HIGH_LIMIT)) {
10589  if (MmAvailablePages > MM_HIGH_LIMIT) {
10590  SizeInPages = MmAvailablePages - MM_HIGH_LIMIT;
10591  }
10592  else {
10593  SizeInPages = 0;
10594  }
10595  }
10596 
10597  if (SizeInPages == 0) {
10598  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
10599  MI_UNLOCK_DYNAMIC_MEMORY_SHARED ();
10600  KeLeaveGuardedRegionThread (Thread);
10601  MmUnlockPageableImageSection (ExPageLockHandle);
10602  ExFreePool (MemoryDescriptorList);
10603  MiReturnCommitment (MdlPageSpan);
10604  ExFreePool (ColoredPageInfoBase);
10605  return NULL;
10606  }
10607 
10608  MM_TRACK_COMMIT (MM_DBG_COMMIT_MDL_PAGES, SizeInPages);
10609 
10610  //
10611  // Charge resident available pages now for all the pages so the PFN lock
10612  // can be released between the loops below. Excess charging is returned
10613  // at the conclusion of the loops.
10614  //
10615 
10616  InterlockedExchangeAddSizeT (&MmMdlPagesAllocated, SizeInPages);
10617 
10618  MI_DECREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (SizeInPages, MM_RESAVAIL_ALLOCATE_FOR_MDL);
10619 
10620  //
10621  // Grab all zeroed (and then free) pages first directly from the
10622  // colored lists to avoid multiple walks down these singly linked lists.
10623  // Then snatch transition pages as needed. In addition to optimizing
10624  // the speed of the removals this also avoids cannibalizing the page
10625  // cache unless it's absolutely needed.
10626  //
10627 
10628  NodePassesLeft = 1;
10629  ColorCount = MmSecondaryColors;
10630  BaseColor = 0;
10631 
10632  Prcb = KeGetCurrentPrcb ();
10633 #if defined (NT_UP)
10634  StartColor = (MI_SYSTEM_PAGE_COLOR++);
10635 #else
10636  StartColor = (Prcb->PageColor++);
10637 #endif
10638  StartColor &= MmSecondaryColorMask;
10639 
10640 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
10641 
10642  if (KeNumberNodes > 1) {
10643 
10644  PKNODE Node;
10645 
10646  Node = KeGetCurrentNode ();
10647 
10648  if ((Node->FreeCount[ZeroedPageList]) ||
10649  (Node->FreeCount[FreePageList])) {
10650 
10651  //
10652  // There are available pages on this node. Restrict search.
10653  //
10654 
10655  NodePassesLeft = 2;
10656  ColorCount = MmSecondaryColorMask + 1;
10657  BaseColor = Node->MmShiftedColor;
10658  ASSERT(ColorCount == MmSecondaryColors / KeNumberNodes);
10659  }
10660  }
10661  else {
10662  Flags &= ~MM_ALLOCATE_FROM_LOCAL_NODE_ONLY;
10663  }
10664 
10665  do {
10666 
10667  //
10668  // Loop: 1st pass restricted to node, 2nd pass unrestricted.
10669  //
10670 
10671 #else
10672  Flags &= ~MM_ALLOCATE_FROM_LOCAL_NODE_ONLY;
10673 #endif
10674 
10675  MemoryList = ZeroedPageList;
10676 
10677  do {
10678 
10679  //
10680  // Scan the zero list and then the free list.
10681  //
10682 
10683  ASSERT (MemoryList <= FreePageList);
10684 
10685  ListHead = MmPageLocationList[MemoryList];
10686 
10687  //
10688  // Initialize the loop iteration controls. Clearly pages
10689  // can be added or removed from the colored lists when we
10690  // deliberately drop the PFN lock below (just to be a good
10691  // citizen), but even if we never released the lock, we wouldn't
10692  // have scanned more than the colorhead count anyway, so
10693  // this is a much better way to go.
10694  //
10695 
10696  ColorHeadsDrained = 0;
10697  PagesExamined = 0;
10698 
10699  ColorHead = &MmFreePagesByColor[MemoryList][BaseColor];
10700  ColoredPageInfo = &ColoredPageInfoBase[BaseColor];
10701  for (Color = 0; Color < ColorCount; Color += 1) {
10702  ASSERT (ColorHead->Count <= MmNumberOfPhysicalPages);
10703  ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan = ColorHead->Count;
10704  if (ColorHead->Count == 0) {
10705  ColorHeadsDrained += 1;
10706  }
10707  ColorHead += 1;
10708  ColoredPageInfo += 1;
10709  }
10710 
10711  Color = BaseColor | StartColor;
10712 
10713  ASSERT (Color < MmSecondaryColors);
10714  do {
10715 
10716  //
10717  // Scan the current list by color.
10718  //
10719 
10720  ColorHead = &MmFreePagesByColor[MemoryList][Color];
10721  ColoredPageInfo = &ColoredPageInfoBase[Color];
10722 
10723  if (NodePassesLeft == 1) {
10724 
10725  //
10726  // Unrestricted search across all colors.
10727  //
10728 
10729  Color += 1;
10730  if (Color >= MmSecondaryColors) {
10731  Color = 0;
10732  }
10733  }
10734 
10735 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
10736 
10737  else {
10738 
10739  //
10740  // Restrict first pass searches to current node.
10741  //
10742 
10743  ASSERT (NodePassesLeft == 2);
10744  Color = BaseColor | ((Color + 1) & MmSecondaryColorMask);
10745  }
10746 
10747 #endif
10748 
10749  if (ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan == 0) {
10750 
10751  //
10752  // This colored list has already been completely
10753  // searched.
10754  //
10755 
10756  continue;
10757  }
10758 
10759  if (ColorHead->Flink == MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
10760 
10761  //
10762  // This colored list is empty.
10763  //
10764 
10765  ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan = 0;
10766  ColorHeadsDrained += 1;
10767  continue;
10768  }
10769 
10770  while (ColorHead->Flink != MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
10771 
10772  ASSERT (ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan != 0);
10773 
10774  ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan -= 1;
10775 
10776  if (ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan == 0) {
10777  ColorHeadsDrained += 1;
10778  }
10779 
10780  PagesExamined += 1;
10781 
10782  Page = ColorHead->Flink;
10783 
10784  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT(Page);
10785 
10786  ASSERT ((MMLISTS)Pfn1->u3.e1.PageLocation == MemoryList);
10787 
10788  //
10789  // See if the page is within the caller's page constraints.
10790  //
10791 
10792  PagePlacementOk = FALSE;
10793 
10794  //
10795  // Since the caller may do anything with these frames
10796  // including mapping them uncached or write combined,
10797  // don't give out frames that are being mapped
10798  // by (cached) superpages.
10799  //
10800 
10801  if ((CacheAttribute == MiCached) ||
10802  (Pfn1->u4.MustBeCached == 0)) {
10803 
10804  LowPage1 = LowPage;
10805  HighPage1 = HighPage;
10806 
10807  do {
10808  if ((Page >= LowPage1) && (Page <= HighPage1)) {
10809  PagePlacementOk = TRUE;
10810  break;
10811  }
10812 
10813  if (SkipPages == 0) {
10814  break;
10815  }
10816 
10817  LowPage1 += SkipPages;
10818  HighPage1 += SkipPages;
10819 
10820  if (HighPage1 > MmHighestPhysicalPage) {
10821  HighPage1 = MmHighestPhysicalPage;
10822  }
10823 
10824  } while (LowPage1 <= MmHighestPhysicalPage);
10825  }
10826 
10827  //
10828  // The Flink and Blink must be nonzero here for the page
10829  // to be on the listhead. Only code that scans the
10830  // MmPhysicalMemoryBlock has to check for the zero case.
10831  //
10832 
10833  ASSERT (Pfn1->u1.Flink != 0);
10834  ASSERT (Pfn1->u2.Blink != 0);
10835 
10836  if (PagePlacementOk == FALSE) {
10837 
10838  if (ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan == 0) {
10839 
10840  //
10841  // No more pages to scan in this colored chain.
10842  //
10843 
10844  break;
10845  }
10846 
10847  //
10848  // If the colored list has more than one entry then
10849  // move this page to the end of this colored list.
10850  //
10851 
10852  PageNextColored = (PFN_NUMBER)Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long;
10853 
10854  if (PageNextColored == MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
10855 
10856  //
10857  // No more pages in this colored chain.
10858  //
10859 
10860  ColoredPageInfo->PagesLeftToScan = 0;
10861  ColorHeadsDrained += 1;
10862  break;
10863  }
10864 
10865  ASSERT (Pfn1->u1.Flink != 0);
10866  ASSERT (Pfn1->u1.Flink != MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10867  ASSERT (Pfn1->u4.PteFrame != MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME);
10868 
10869  PfnNextColored = MI_PFN_ELEMENT(PageNextColored);
10870  ASSERT ((MMLISTS)PfnNextColored->u3.e1.PageLocation == MemoryList);
10871  ASSERT (PfnNextColored->u4.PteFrame != MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME);
10872 
10873  //
10874  // Adjust the free page list so Page
10875  // follows PageNextFlink.
10876  //
10877 
10878  PageNextFlink = Pfn1->u1.Flink;
10879  PfnNextFlink = MI_PFN_ELEMENT(PageNextFlink);
10880 
10881  ASSERT ((MMLISTS)PfnNextFlink->u3.e1.PageLocation == MemoryList);
10882  ASSERT (PfnNextFlink->u4.PteFrame != MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME);
10883 
10884  PfnLastColored = ColorHead->Blink;
10885  ASSERT (PfnLastColored != (PMMPFN)MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10886  ASSERT (PfnLastColored->OriginalPte.u.Long == MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10887  ASSERT (PfnLastColored->u4.PteFrame != MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME);
10888  ASSERT (PfnLastColored->u2.Blink != MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10889 
10890  ASSERT ((MMLISTS)PfnLastColored->u3.e1.PageLocation == MemoryList);
10891  PageLastColored = MI_PFN_ELEMENT_TO_INDEX (PfnLastColored);
10892 
10893  if (ListHead->Flink == Page) {
10894 
10895  ASSERT (Pfn1->u2.Blink == MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10896  ASSERT (ListHead->Blink != Page);
10897 
10898  ListHead->Flink = PageNextFlink;
10899 
10900  PfnNextFlink->u2.Blink = MM_EMPTY_LIST;
10901  }
10902  else {
10903 
10904  ASSERT (Pfn1->u2.Blink != MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10905  ASSERT ((MMLISTS)(MI_PFN_ELEMENT((MI_PFN_ELEMENT(Pfn1->u2.Blink)->u1.Flink)))->u4.PteFrame != MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME);
10906  ASSERT ((MMLISTS)(MI_PFN_ELEMENT((MI_PFN_ELEMENT(Pfn1->u2.Blink)->u1.Flink)))->u3.e1.PageLocation == MemoryList);
10907 
10908  MI_PFN_ELEMENT(Pfn1->u2.Blink)->u1.Flink = PageNextFlink;
10909  PfnNextFlink->u2.Blink = Pfn1->u2.Blink;
10910  }
10911 
10912 #if DBG
10913  if (PfnLastColored->u1.Flink == MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
10914  ASSERT (ListHead->Blink == PageLastColored);
10915  }
10916 #endif
10917 
10918  Pfn1->u1.Flink = PfnLastColored->u1.Flink;
10919  Pfn1->u2.Blink = PageLastColored;
10920 
10921  if (ListHead->Blink == PageLastColored) {
10922  ListHead->Blink = Page;
10923  }
10924 
10925  //
10926  // Adjust the colored chains.
10927  //
10928 
10929  if (PfnLastColored->u1.Flink != MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
10930  ASSERT (MI_PFN_ELEMENT(PfnLastColored->u1.Flink)->u4.PteFrame != MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME);
10931  ASSERT ((MMLISTS)(MI_PFN_ELEMENT(PfnLastColored->u1.Flink)->u3.e1.PageLocation) == MemoryList);
10932  MI_PFN_ELEMENT(PfnLastColored->u1.Flink)->u2.Blink = Page;
10933  }
10934 
10935  PfnLastColored->u1.Flink = Page;
10936 
10937  ColorHead->Flink = PageNextColored;
10938  PfnNextColored->u4.PteFrame = MM_EMPTY_LIST;
10939 
10940  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = MM_EMPTY_LIST;
10941  Pfn1->u4.PteFrame = PageLastColored;
10942 
10943  ASSERT (PfnLastColored->OriginalPte.u.Long == MM_EMPTY_LIST);
10944  PfnLastColored->OriginalPte.u.Long = Page;
10945  ColorHead->Blink = Pfn1;
10946 
10947  continue;
10948  }
10949 
10950  found += 1;
10951  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e1.ReadInProgress == 0);
10952  MiUnlinkFreeOrZeroedPage (Pfn1);
10953 
10954  Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount = 1;
10955  Pfn1->u2.ShareCount = 1;
10956  MI_SET_PFN_DELETED(Pfn1);
10957  Pfn1->u4.PteFrame = MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME;
10958  Pfn1->u3.e1.PageLocation = ActiveAndValid;
10959 
10960  CacheTypesFound |= (1 << Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute);
10961 
10962  Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute = CacheAttribute;
10963 
10964  Pfn1->u3.e1.StartOfAllocation = 1;
10965  Pfn1->u3.e1.EndOfAllocation = 1;
10966  Pfn1->u4.VerifierAllocation = 0;
10967  Pfn1->u3.e1.LargeSessionAllocation = 0;
10968 
10969  //
10970  // Add free pages to the list of pages to be
10971  // zeroed before returning.
10972  //
10973 
10974  if ((MemoryList == FreePageList) &&
10975  ((Flags & MM_DONT_ZERO_ALLOCATION) == 0)) {
10976 
10977  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = (ULONG_PTR) ColoredPageInfo->PfnAllocation;
10978  ColoredPageInfo->PfnAllocation = Pfn1;
10979  ColoredPageInfo->PagesQueued += 1;
10980  ZeroCount += 1;
10981  }
10982  else {
10983  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = MM_DEMAND_ZERO_WRITE_PTE;
10984  }
10985 
10986  *MdlPage = Page;
10987  MdlPage += 1;
10988 
10989  if (found == SizeInPages) {
10990 
10991  //
10992  // All the pages requested are available.
10993  //
10994 
10995 #if DBG
10996  FinishedCount = 0;
10997  for (i = 0; i < ColorCount; i += 1) {
10998  if (ColoredPageInfoBase[i + BaseColor].PagesLeftToScan == 0) {
10999  FinishedCount += 1;
11000  }
11001  }
11002  ASSERT (FinishedCount == ColorHeadsDrained);
11003 #endif
11004 
11005  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11006  goto pass2_done;
11007  }
11008 
11009  //
11010  // March on to the next colored chain so the overall
11011  // allocation round-robins the page colors.
11012  //
11013 
11014  PagesExamined = PAGE_SIZE;
11015  break;
11016  }
11017 
11018  //
11019  // If we've held the PFN lock for a while, release it to
11020  // give DPCs and other processors a chance to run.
11021  //
11022 
11023  if (PagesExamined >= PAGE_SIZE) {
11024  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11025  PagesExamined = 0;
11026  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11027  }
11028 
11029  //
11030  // Systems utilizing memory compression may have more
11031  // pages on the zero, free and standby lists than we
11032  // want to give out. The same is true when machines
11033  // are low on memory - we don't want this thread to gobble
11034  // up the pages from every modified write that completes
11035  // because that would starve waiting threads.
11036  //
11037  // Explicitly check MmAvailablePages instead (and recheck
11038  // whenever the PFN lock is released and reacquired).
11039  //
11040 
11041  if (MmAvailablePages < MM_HIGH_LIMIT) {
11042  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11043  goto pass2_done;
11044  }
11045 
11046  } while (ColorHeadsDrained != ColorCount);
11047 
11048  //
11049  // Release the PFN lock to give DPCs and other processors
11050  // a chance to run. Nothing magic about the instructions
11051  // between the unlock and the relock.
11052  //
11053 
11054  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11055 
11056  //
11057  // Increment the start color so the next pass will keep walking
11058  // forwards through the color choices.
11059  //
11060 
11061  StartColor = Color + 1;
11062  StartColor &= MmSecondaryColorMask;
11063 
11064 #if DBG
11065  FinishedCount = 0;
11066  for (i = 0; i < ColorCount; i += 1) {
11067  if (ColoredPageInfoBase[BaseColor + i].PagesLeftToScan == 0) {
11068  FinishedCount += 1;
11069  }
11070  }
11071  ASSERT (FinishedCount == ColorHeadsDrained);
11072 #endif
11073 
11074  MemoryList += 1;
11075 
11076  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11077 
11078  } while (MemoryList <= FreePageList);
11079 
11080 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
11081 
11082  if (Flags & MM_ALLOCATE_FROM_LOCAL_NODE_ONLY) {
11083  break;
11084  }
11085 
11086  //
11087  // Expand range to all colors for next pass.
11088  //
11089 
11090  ColorCount = MmSecondaryColors;
11091  BaseColor = 0;
11092 
11093  NodePassesLeft -= 1;
11094 
11095  } while (NodePassesLeft != 0);
11096 
11097 #endif
11098 
11099  //
11100  // Briefly release the PFN lock to give DPCs and other processors
11101  // a time slice.
11102  //
11103 
11104  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11105 
11106  if (Flags & MM_ALLOCATE_FROM_LOCAL_NODE_ONLY) {
11107  BaseColor = KeGetCurrentNode()->Color;
11108  }
11109  else {
11110  BaseColor = 0;
11111  }
11112 
11113  //
11114  // Walk the transition lists looking for pages satisfying the
11115  // constraints as walking the physical memory block can be draining.
11116  //
11117 
11118  for (ListHead = &MmStandbyPageListByPriority[0];
11119  ListHead < &MmStandbyPageListByPriority[MI_PFN_PRIORITIES];
11120  ListHead += 1) {
11121 
11122  if (ListHead->Flink == MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
11123  continue;
11124  }
11125 
11126  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11127 
11128  for (Page = ListHead->Flink; Page != MM_EMPTY_LIST; Page = NextPage) {
11129 
11130  //
11131  // Systems utilizing memory compression may have more
11132  // pages on the zero, free and standby lists than we
11133  // want to give out. The same is true when machines
11134  // are low on memory - we don't want this thread to gobble
11135  // up the pages from every modified write that completes
11136  // because that would starve waiting threads.
11137  //
11138  // Explicitly check MmAvailablePages instead (and recheck whenever
11139  // the PFN lock is released and reacquired).
11140  //
11141 
11142  if (MmAvailablePages < MM_HIGH_LIMIT) {
11143  ListHead = &MmStandbyPageListByPriority[MI_PFN_PRIORITIES];
11144  break;
11145  }
11146 
11147  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (Page);
11148  NextPage = Pfn1->u1.Flink;
11149 
11150  //
11151  // Since the caller may do anything with these frames including
11152  // mapping them uncached or write combined, don't give out frames
11153  // that are being mapped by (cached) superpages.
11154  //
11155 
11156  if ((CacheAttribute != MiCached) && (Pfn1->u4.MustBeCached == 1)) {
11157  continue;
11158  }
11159 
11160  LowPage1 = LowPage;
11161  HighPage1 = HighPage;
11162  PagePlacementOk = FALSE;
11163 
11164  do {
11165  if ((Page >= LowPage1) && (Page <= HighPage1)) {
11166 
11167  if (Flags & MM_ALLOCATE_FROM_LOCAL_NODE_ONLY) {
11168  if (BaseColor == Pfn1->u3.e1.PageColor) {
11169  PagePlacementOk = TRUE;
11170  }
11171  }
11172  else {
11173  PagePlacementOk = TRUE;
11174  }
11175 
11176  break;
11177  }
11178 
11179  if (SkipPages == 0) {
11180  break;
11181  }
11182 
11183  LowPage1 += SkipPages;
11184  HighPage1 += SkipPages;
11185 
11186  if (HighPage1 > MmHighestPhysicalPage) {
11187  HighPage1 = MmHighestPhysicalPage;
11188  }
11189 
11190  } while (LowPage1 <= MmHighestPhysicalPage);
11191 
11192  if (PagePlacementOk == TRUE) {
11193 
11194  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e1.ReadInProgress == 0);
11195 
11196  found += 1;
11197 
11198  //
11199  // This page is in the desired range - grab it.
11200  //
11201 
11202  MiUnlinkPageFromList (Pfn1);
11203  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount == 0);
11204  MiRestoreTransitionPte (Pfn1);
11205 
11206  Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount = 1;
11207  Pfn1->u2.ShareCount = 1;
11208  MI_SET_PFN_DELETED(Pfn1);
11209  Pfn1->u4.PteFrame = MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME;
11210  Pfn1->u3.e1.PageLocation = ActiveAndValid;
11211 
11212  CacheTypesFound |= (1 << Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute);
11213 
11214  Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute = CacheAttribute;
11215  Pfn1->u3.e1.StartOfAllocation = 1;
11216  Pfn1->u3.e1.EndOfAllocation = 1;
11217  Pfn1->u4.VerifierAllocation = 0;
11218  Pfn1->u3.e1.LargeSessionAllocation = 0;
11219 
11220  //
11221  // Add standby pages to the list of pages to be
11222  // zeroed before returning.
11223  //
11224 
11225  if ((Flags & MM_DONT_ZERO_ALLOCATION) == 0) {
11226 
11227  ColoredPageInfo = &ColoredPageInfoBase[MI_GET_COLOR_FROM_LIST_ENTRY (Page, Pfn1)];
11228  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = (ULONG_PTR) ColoredPageInfo->PfnAllocation;
11229  ColoredPageInfo->PfnAllocation = Pfn1;
11230  ColoredPageInfo->PagesQueued += 1;
11231  ZeroCount += 1;
11232  }
11233  else {
11234  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = MM_DEMAND_ZERO_WRITE_PTE;
11235  }
11236 
11237  *MdlPage = Page;
11238  MdlPage += 1;
11239 
11240  if (found == SizeInPages) {
11241 
11242  //
11243  // All the pages requested are available.
11244  //
11245 
11246  ListHead = &MmStandbyPageListByPriority[MI_PFN_PRIORITIES];
11247  break;
11248  }
11249  }
11250  }
11251 
11252  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11253  }
11254 
11255 pass2_done:
11256 
11257  //
11258  // The full amount was charged up front - remove any excess now.
11259  //
11260 
11261  MI_INCREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (SizeInPages - found, MM_RESAVAIL_FREE_FOR_MDL_EXCESS);
11262 
11263  InterlockedExchangeAddSizeT (&MmMdlPagesAllocated, 0 - (SizeInPages - found));
11264 
11265  MI_UNLOCK_DYNAMIC_MEMORY_SHARED ();
11266  KeLeaveGuardedRegionThread (Thread);
11267 
11268  MmUnlockPageableImageSection (ExPageLockHandle);
11269 
11270  if (found != MdlPageSpan) {
11271  ASSERT (found < MdlPageSpan);
11272  MiReturnCommitment (MdlPageSpan - found);
11273  MM_TRACK_COMMIT (MM_DBG_COMMIT_RETURN_AWE_EXCESS, MdlPageSpan - found);
11274  }
11275 
11276  if (found == 0) {
11277  ExFreePool (ColoredPageInfoBase);
11278  ExFreePool (MemoryDescriptorList);
11279  return NULL;
11280  }
11281 
11282  //
11283  // Update the color to the last one allocated (excluding any repurposed
11284  // transition pages) so subsequent allocations continue to round-robin
11285  // fairly. Since the local color has already been incremented, carefully
11286  // decrement making sure not to cross nodes.
11287  //
11288 
11289  if ((Color & MmSecondaryColorMask) != 0) {
11290  Color -= 1;
11291  }
11292  else {
11293 #if defined(MI_MULTINODE)
11294  if (KeNumberNodes > 1) {
11295  if (NodePassesLeft == 1) {
11296  if (Color == 0) {
11297  Color = MmSecondaryColors - 1;
11298  }
11299  else {
11300  Color -= 1;
11301  }
11302  }
11303  else {
11304  Color |= MmSecondaryColorMask;
11305  }
11306  }
11307  else
11308 #endif
11309  Color |= MmSecondaryColorMask;
11310  }
11311 
11312 #if defined (NT_UP)
11313  MI_SYSTEM_PAGE_COLOR = Color;
11314 #else
11315  Prcb->PageColor = Color;
11316 #endif
11317 
11318  MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount = (ULONG)(found << PAGE_SHIFT);
11319 
11320  if (found != SizeInPages) {
11321  *MdlPage = MM_EMPTY_LIST;
11322  }
11323 
11324  //
11325  // If we are providing cached pages then flush any stale TB entries now.
11326  // Any needed zeroing below will then use cached mappings as will our
11327  // caller.
11328  //
11329 
11330  if (CacheAttribute == MiCached) {
11331 
11332  //
11333  // If all the allocated pages were either not mapped or were last
11334  // mapped as cached, then skip the TB flush as there can be no
11335  // conflicting attributes with the new mapping.
11336  //
11337 
11338  if (CacheTypesFound & ~((1 << MiCached) | (1 << MiNotMapped))) {
11339  MI_FLUSH_TB_FOR_CACHED_ATTRIBUTE ();
11340  }
11341  }
11342 
11343  if (ZeroCount != 0) {
11344 
11345  //
11346  // Flush the entire TB since we overwrote the initial PFN attributes
11347  // above with MiNotMapped. This ensures that the zeroing below can
11348  // use any attribute (it will use cached).
11349  //
11350 
11351  if (CacheAttribute != MiCached) {
11352  MI_FLUSH_ENTIRE_TB_FOR_ATTRIBUTE_CHANGE (MiNonCached);
11353  }
11354 
11355  //
11356  // Zero all the free & standby pages, fanning out the work. This
11357  // is done even on UP machines because the worker thread code maps
11358  // large MDLs and is thus better performing than zeroing a single
11359  // page at a time.
11360  //
11361 
11362  MiZeroInParallel (ColoredPageInfoBase);
11363 
11364  //
11365  // Denote that no pages are left to be zeroed because in addition
11366  // to zeroing them, we have reset all their OriginalPte fields
11367  // to demand zero so they cannot be walked by the zeroing loop
11368  // below.
11369  //
11370 
11371  ZeroCount = 0;
11372  }
11373 
11374  //
11375  // Flush the entire TB since we overwrote the initial PFN attributes
11376  // above with MiNotMapped. Even if we didn't have to zero any of the
11377  // pages above, we still need to get rid of any stale (ie: like system
11378  // PTE mappings to the pages in their previous lives) TB entries since
11379  // our caller may choose to use any attribute.
11380  //
11381 
11382  if (CacheAttribute != MiCached) {
11383  MI_FLUSH_ENTIRE_TB_FOR_ATTRIBUTE_CHANGE (MiNonCached);
11384  }
11385 
11386  ExFreePool (ColoredPageInfoBase);
11387 
11388  //
11389  // If the number of pages allocated was substantially less than the
11390  // initial request amount, attempt to allocate a smaller MDL to save
11391  // pool.
11392  //
11393 
11394  if ((MdlPageSpan - found) > ((4 * PAGE_SIZE) / sizeof (PFN_NUMBER))) {
11395 
11396  MemoryDescriptorList2 = MmCreateMdl (NULL,
11397  NULL,
11398  found << PAGE_SHIFT);
11399 
11400  if (MemoryDescriptorList2 != NULL) {
11401 
11402  RtlCopyMemory ((PVOID)(MemoryDescriptorList2 + 1),
11403  (PVOID)(MemoryDescriptorList + 1),
11404  found * sizeof (PFN_NUMBER));
11405 
11406  ExFreePool (MemoryDescriptorList);
11407  MemoryDescriptorList = MemoryDescriptorList2;
11408  }
11409  }
11410 
11411 #if DBG
11412  //
11413  // Ensure all pages are within the caller's page constraints.
11414  //
11415 
11416  MdlPage = (PPFN_NUMBER)(MemoryDescriptorList + 1);
11417  LastMdlPage = MdlPage + found;
11418 
11419  LowPage = (PFN_NUMBER)(LowAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
11420  HighPage = (PFN_NUMBER)(HighAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
11421  Process = PsGetCurrentProcess ();
11422 
11423  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle (ExPageLockHandle);
11424 
11425  while (MdlPage < LastMdlPage) {
11426  Page = *MdlPage;
11427  PagePlacementOk = FALSE;
11428  LowPage1 = LowPage;
11429  HighPage1 = HighPage;
11430 
11431  do {
11432  if ((Page >= LowPage1) && (Page <= HighPage1)) {
11433  PagePlacementOk = TRUE;
11434  break;
11435  }
11436 
11437  if (SkipPages == 0) {
11438  break;
11439  }
11440 
11441  LowPage1 += SkipPages;
11442  HighPage1 += SkipPages;
11443 
11444  if (LowPage1 > MmHighestPhysicalPage) {
11445  break;
11446  }
11447  if (HighPage1 > MmHighestPhysicalPage) {
11448  HighPage1 = MmHighestPhysicalPage;
11449  }
11450  } while (TRUE);
11451 
11452  ASSERT (PagePlacementOk == TRUE);
11453  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT(*MdlPage);
11454  ASSERT (Pfn1->u4.PteFrame == MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME);
11455  MdlPage += 1;
11456  }
11457 
11458  MmUnlockPageableImageSection (ExPageLockHandle);
11459 
11460 #endif
11461 
11462  MemoryDescriptorList->Process = NULL;
11463 
11464  //
11465  // Mark the MDL's pages as locked so the the kernelmode caller can
11466  // map the MDL using MmMapLockedPages* without asserting.
11467  //
11468 
11469  MemoryDescriptorList->MdlFlags |= MDL_PAGES_LOCKED;
11470 
11471  return MemoryDescriptorList;
11472 }
11473 
11474 
11475 PMDL
11476 MmAllocatePagesForMdl (
11477  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS LowAddress,
11478  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS HighAddress,
11479  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS SkipBytes,
11480  __in SIZE_T TotalBytes
11481  )
11482 
11483 /*++
11484 
11485 Routine Description:
11486 
11487  This routine searches the PFN database for free, zeroed or standby pages
11488  to satisfy the request. This does not map the pages - it just allocates
11489  them and puts them into an MDL. It is expected that our caller will
11490  map the MDL as needed.
11491 
11492  NOTE: this routine may return an MDL mapping a smaller number of bytes
11493  than the amount requested. It is the caller's responsibility to check the
11494  MDL upon return for the size actually allocated.
11495 
11496  These pages comprise physical non-paged memory and are zero-filled.
11497 
11498  This routine is designed to be used by an AGP driver to obtain physical
11499  memory in a specified range since hardware may provide substantial
11500  performance wins depending on where the backing memory is allocated.
11501 
11502  Because the caller may use these pages for a noncached mapping, care is
11503  taken to never allocate any pages that reside in a large page (in order
11504  to prevent TB incoherency of the same page being mapped by multiple
11505  translations with different attributes).
11506 
11507 Arguments:
11508 
11509  LowAddress - Supplies the low physical address of the first range that
11510  the allocated pages can come from.
11511 
11512  HighAddress - Supplies the high physical address of the first range that
11513  the allocated pages can come from.
11514 
11515  SkipBytes - Number of bytes to skip (from the Low Address) to get to the
11516  next physical address range that allocated pages can come from.
11517 
11518  TotalBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to allocate.
11519 
11520 Return Value:
11521 
11522  MDL - An MDL mapping a range of pages in the specified range.
11523  This may map less memory than the caller requested if the full amount
11524  is not currently available.
11525 
11526  NULL - No pages in the specified range OR not enough virtually contiguous
11527  nonpaged pool for the MDL is available at this time.
11528 
11529 Environment:
11530 
11531  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
11532 
11533 --*/
11534 
11535 {
11536  return MiAllocatePagesForMdl (LowAddress,
11537  HighAddress,
11538  SkipBytes,
11539  TotalBytes,
11540  MiNotMapped,
11541  0);
11542 }
11543 
11544 
11545 PMDL
11546 MmAllocatePagesForMdlEx (
11547  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS LowAddress,
11548  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS HighAddress,
11549  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS SkipBytes,
11550  __in SIZE_T TotalBytes,
11551  __in MEMORY_CACHING_TYPE CacheType,
11552  __in ULONG Flags
11553  )
11554 
11555 /*++
11556 
11557 Routine Description:
11558 
11559  This routine searches the PFN database for free, zeroed or standby pages
11560  to satisfy the request. This does not map the pages - it just allocates
11561  them and puts them into an MDL. It is expected that our caller will
11562  map the MDL as needed.
11563 
11564  NOTE: this routine may return an MDL mapping a smaller number of bytes
11565  than the amount requested. It is the caller's responsibility to check the
11566  MDL upon return for the size actually allocated.
11567 
11568  These pages comprise physical non-paged memory and are zero-filled.
11569 
11570  This routine is designed to be used by an AGP driver to obtain physical
11571  memory in a specified range since hardware may provide substantial
11572  performance wins depending on where the backing memory is allocated.
11573 
11574  Because the caller may use these pages for a noncached mapping, care is
11575  taken to never allocate any pages that reside in a large page (in order
11576  to prevent TB incoherency of the same page being mapped by multiple
11577  translations with different attributes).
11578 
11579 Arguments:
11580 
11581  LowAddress - Supplies the low physical address of the first range that
11582  the allocated pages can come from.
11583 
11584  HighAddress - Supplies the high physical address of the first range that
11585  the allocated pages can come from.
11586 
11587  SkipBytes - Number of bytes to skip (from the Low Address) to get to the
11588  next physical address range that allocated pages can come from.
11589 
11590  TotalBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to allocate.
11591 
11592  CacheType - Supplies the cache type the caller desires for these pages.
11593 
11594  Flags - Supplies flags passed by the caller, currently there are 2:
11595  MM_DONT_ZERO_ALLOCATION and MM_ALLOCATE_FROM_LOCAL_NODE_ONLY
11596 
11597 Return Value:
11598 
11599  MDL - An MDL mapping a range of pages in the specified range.
11600  This may map less memory than the caller requested if the full amount
11601  is not currently available.
11602 
11603  NULL - No pages in the specified range OR not enough virtually contiguous
11604  nonpaged pool for the MDL is available at this time.
11605 
11606 Environment:
11607 
11608  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
11609 
11610 --*/
11611 
11612 {
11613  MI_PFN_CACHE_ATTRIBUTE CacheAttribute;
11614 
11615  if (CacheType > MmWriteCombined) {
11616  CacheAttribute = MiNotMapped;
11617  }
11618  else {
11619  CacheAttribute = MI_TRANSLATE_CACHETYPE (CacheType, FALSE);
11620  }
11621 
11622  if (Flags & ~(MM_DONT_ZERO_ALLOCATION | MM_ALLOCATE_FROM_LOCAL_NODE_ONLY)) {
11623 
11624  //
11625  // Don't allow external callers to specify internal flags (like
11626  // MI_ALLOCATION_IS_AWE).
11627  //
11628 
11629  return NULL;
11630  }
11631 
11632  return MiAllocatePagesForMdl (LowAddress,
11633  HighAddress,
11634  SkipBytes,
11635  TotalBytes,
11636  CacheAttribute,
11637  Flags);
11638 }
11639 
11640 
11641 VOID
11642 MmFreePagesFromMdl (
11643  __in PMDL MemoryDescriptorList
11644  )
11645 
11646 /*++
11647 
11648 Routine Description:
11649 
11650  This routine walks the argument MDL freeing each physical page back to
11651  the PFN database. This is designed to free pages acquired via
11652  MmAllocatePagesForMdl only.
11653 
11654 Arguments:
11655 
11656  MemoryDescriptorList - Supplies an MDL which contains the pages to be freed.
11657 
11658 Return Value:
11659 
11660  None.
11661 
11662 Environment:
11663 
11664  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
11665 
11666 --*/
11667 {
11668  PMMPFN Pfn1;
11669  KIRQL OldIrql;
11670  PVOID StartingAddress;
11671  PVOID AlignedVa;
11672  PPFN_NUMBER Page;
11673  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages;
11674  PFN_NUMBER TotalPages;
11675  PFN_NUMBER DeltaPages;
11676  LONG EntryCount;
11677  LONG OriginalCount;
11678 
11679  ASSERT (KeGetCurrentIrql() <= APC_LEVEL);
11680 
11681  DeltaPages = 0;
11682 
11683  Page = (PPFN_NUMBER)(MemoryDescriptorList + 1);
11684 
11685  ASSERT ((MemoryDescriptorList->MdlFlags & MDL_IO_SPACE) == 0);
11686 
11687  ASSERT (((ULONG_PTR)MemoryDescriptorList->StartVa & (PAGE_SIZE - 1)) == 0);
11688  AlignedVa = (PVOID)MemoryDescriptorList->StartVa;
11689 
11690  StartingAddress = (PVOID)((PCHAR)AlignedVa +
11691  MemoryDescriptorList->ByteOffset);
11692 
11693  NumberOfPages = ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES(StartingAddress,
11694  MemoryDescriptorList->ByteCount);
11695 
11696  TotalPages = NumberOfPages;
11697 
11698  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle (ExPageLockHandle);
11699 
11700  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11701 
11702  do {
11703 
11704 #pragma prefast(suppress: 2000, "SAL 1.2 needed for accurate MDL struct annotation.")
11705  if (*Page == MM_EMPTY_LIST) {
11706 
11707  //
11708  // There are no more locked pages.
11709  //
11710 
11711  break;
11712  }
11713 
11714  ASSERT (MI_IS_PFN (*Page));
11715  ASSERT (*Page <= MmHighestPhysicalPage);
11716 
11717  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (*Page);
11718  ASSERT (Pfn1->u2.ShareCount == 1);
11719  ASSERT (MI_IS_PFN_DELETED (Pfn1) == TRUE);
11720  ASSERT (MI_PFN_IS_AWE (Pfn1) == TRUE);
11721 
11722  if (Pfn1->u4.PteFrame != MI_MAGIC_AWE_PTEFRAME) {
11723  KeBugCheckEx (MEMORY_MANAGEMENT,
11724  0x1236,
11725  (ULONG_PTR) MemoryDescriptorList,
11726  (ULONG_PTR) Page,
11727  *Page);
11728  }
11729 
11730  Pfn1->u3.e1.StartOfAllocation = 0;
11731  Pfn1->u3.e1.EndOfAllocation = 0;
11732  Pfn1->u2.ShareCount = 0;
11733 
11734  //
11735  // If the frame was never mapped, then default to calling it cached
11736  // to reduce TB invalidates.
11737  //
11738 
11739  if (Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute == MiNotMapped) {
11740  Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute = MiCached;
11741  }
11742 
11743  Pfn1->u4.PteFrame -= 1;
11744 #if DBG
11745  Pfn1->u3.e1.PageLocation = StandbyPageList;
11746 #endif
11747 
11748  if (Pfn1->u4.AweAllocation == 1) {
11749 
11750  do {
11751 
11752  EntryCount = ReadForWriteAccess (&Pfn1->AweReferenceCount);
11753 
11754  ASSERT ((LONG)EntryCount > 0);
11755  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount != 0);
11756 
11757  OriginalCount = InterlockedCompareExchange (&Pfn1->AweReferenceCount,
11758  EntryCount - 1,
11759  EntryCount);
11760 
11761  if (OriginalCount == EntryCount) {
11762 
11763  //
11764  // This thread can be racing against other threads
11765  // calling MmUnlockPages. All threads can safely do
11766  // interlocked decrements on the "AWE reference count".
11767  // Whichever thread drives it to zero is responsible for
11768  // decrementing the actual PFN reference count (which may
11769  // be greater than 1 due to other non-AWE API calls being
11770  // used on the same page). The thread that drives this
11771  // reference count to zero must put the page on the actual
11772  // freelist at that time and decrement various resident
11773  // available and commitment counters also.
11774  //
11775 
11776  if (OriginalCount == 1) {
11777 
11778  //
11779  // This thread has driven the AWE reference count to
11780  // zero so it must initiate a decrement of the PFN
11781  // reference count (while holding the PFN lock), etc.
11782  //
11783  // This path should be the frequent one since typically
11784  // I/Os complete before these types of pages are
11785  // freed by the app.
11786  //
11787 
11788  MiDecrementReferenceCountForAwePage (Pfn1, TRUE);
11789  }
11790 
11791  break;
11792  }
11793  } while (TRUE);
11794  }
11795  else {
11796  MiDecrementReferenceCountInline (Pfn1, *Page);
11797  DeltaPages += 1;
11798  }
11799 
11800  *Page++ = MM_EMPTY_LIST;
11801 
11802  //
11803  // Nothing magic about the divisor here - just releasing the PFN lock
11804  // periodically to allow other processors and DPCs a chance to execute.
11805  //
11806 
11807  if ((NumberOfPages & 0xF) == 0) {
11808 
11809  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11810 
11811  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11812  }
11813 
11814  NumberOfPages -= 1;
11815 
11816  } while (NumberOfPages != 0);
11817 
11818  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
11819 
11820  MmUnlockPageableImageSection (ExPageLockHandle);
11821 
11822  if (DeltaPages != 0) {
11823  MI_INCREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (DeltaPages, MM_RESAVAIL_FREE_FROM_MDL);
11824  InterlockedExchangeAddSizeT (&MmMdlPagesAllocated, 0 - DeltaPages);
11825  MiReturnCommitment (DeltaPages);
11826  MM_TRACK_COMMIT (MM_DBG_COMMIT_RETURN_MDL_PAGES, DeltaPages);
11827  }
11828 
11829  MemoryDescriptorList->MdlFlags &= ~MDL_PAGES_LOCKED;
11830 }
11831 
11832 
11833 NTSTATUS
11834 MmMapUserAddressesToPage (
11835  __in_bcount(NumberOfBytes) PVOID BaseAddress,
11836  __in SIZE_T NumberOfBytes,
11837  __in PVOID PageAddress
11838  )
11839 
11840 /*++
11841 
11842 Routine Description:
11843 
11844  This function maps a range of addresses in a physical memory VAD to the
11845  specified page address. This is typically used by a driver to nicely
11846  remove an application's access to things like video memory when the
11847  application is not responding to requests to relinquish it.
11848 
11849  Note the entire range must be currently mapped (ie, all the PTEs must
11850  be valid) by the caller.
11851 
11852 Arguments:
11853 
11854  BaseAddress - Supplies the base virtual address where the physical
11855  address is mapped.
11856 
11857  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to remap to the new address.
11858 
11859  PageAddress - Supplies the virtual address of the page this is remapped to.
11860  This must be nonpaged memory.
11861 
11862 Return Value:
11863 
11864  Various NTSTATUS codes.
11865 
11866 Environment:
11867 
11868  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
11869 
11870 --*/
11871 
11872 {
11873  PMMVAD Vad;
11874  PMMPTE PointerPte;
11875  MMPTE PteContents;
11876  PMMPTE LastPte;
11877  PETHREAD Thread;
11878  PEPROCESS Process;
11879  NTSTATUS Status;
11880  PVOID EndingAddress;
11881  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameNumber;
11882  SIZE_T NumberOfPtes;
11883  PHYSICAL_ADDRESS PhysicalAddress;
11884  KIRQL OldIrql;
11885 
11886  PAGED_CODE();
11887 
11888  if (BaseAddress > MM_HIGHEST_USER_ADDRESS) {
11889  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER_1;
11890  }
11891 
11892  if ((ULONG_PTR)BaseAddress + NumberOfBytes > (ULONG64)MM_HIGHEST_USER_ADDRESS) {
11893  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER_2;
11894  }
11895 
11896  Thread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
11897  Process = PsGetCurrentProcessByThread (Thread);
11898 
11899  EndingAddress = (PVOID)((PCHAR)BaseAddress + NumberOfBytes - 1);
11900 
11901  LOCK_ADDRESS_SPACE (Process);
11902 
11903  //
11904  // Make sure the address space was not deleted.
11905  //
11906 
11907  if (Process->Flags & PS_PROCESS_FLAGS_VM_DELETED) {
11908  Status = STATUS_PROCESS_IS_TERMINATING;
11909  goto ErrorReturn;
11910  }
11911 
11912  Vad = (PMMVAD)MiLocateAddress (BaseAddress);
11913 
11914  if (Vad == NULL) {
11915 
11916  //
11917  // No virtual address descriptor located.
11918  //
11919 
11920  Status = STATUS_MEMORY_NOT_ALLOCATED;
11921  goto ErrorReturn;
11922  }
11923 
11924  if (NumberOfBytes == 0) {
11925 
11926  //
11927  // If the region size is specified as 0, the base address
11928  // must be the starting address for the region. The entire VAD
11929  // will then be re-pointed.
11930  //
11931 
11932  if (MI_VA_TO_VPN (BaseAddress) != Vad->StartingVpn) {
11933  Status = STATUS_FREE_VM_NOT_AT_BASE;
11934  goto ErrorReturn;
11935  }
11936 
11937  BaseAddress = MI_VPN_TO_VA (Vad->StartingVpn);
11938  EndingAddress = MI_VPN_TO_VA_ENDING (Vad->EndingVpn);
11939  NumberOfBytes = (PCHAR)EndingAddress - (PCHAR)BaseAddress + 1;
11940  }
11941 
11942  //
11943  // Found the associated virtual address descriptor.
11944  //
11945 
11946  if (Vad->EndingVpn < MI_VA_TO_VPN (EndingAddress)) {
11947 
11948  //
11949  // The entire range to remap is not contained within a single
11950  // virtual address descriptor. Return an error.
11951  //
11952 
11953  Status = STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER_2;
11954  goto ErrorReturn;
11955  }
11956 
11957  if (Vad->u.VadFlags.VadType != VadDevicePhysicalMemory) {
11958 
11959  //
11960  // The virtual address descriptor is not a physical mapping.
11961  //
11962 
11963  Status = STATUS_INVALID_ADDRESS;
11964  goto ErrorReturn;
11965  }
11966 
11967  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (BaseAddress);
11968  LastPte = MiGetPteAddress (EndingAddress);
11969  NumberOfPtes = LastPte - PointerPte + 1;
11970 
11971  //
11972  // Lock down because the PFN lock is going to be acquired shortly.
11973  //
11974 
11975  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle(ExPageLockHandle);
11976 
11977  LOCK_WS_UNSAFE (Thread, Process);
11978 
11979  PhysicalAddress = MmGetPhysicalAddress (PageAddress);
11980  PageFrameNumber = (PFN_NUMBER)(PhysicalAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
11981 
11982  PteContents = *PointerPte;
11983  PteContents.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber = PageFrameNumber;
11984 
11985 #if DBG
11986 
11987  //
11988  // All the PTEs must be valid or the filling will corrupt the
11989  // UsedPageTableCounts.
11990  //
11991 
11992  do {
11993  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 1);
