11994  PointerPte += 1;
11995  } while (PointerPte < LastPte);
11996  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (BaseAddress);
11997 #endif
11998 
11999  //
12000  // Fill the PTEs and flush at the end - no race here because it doesn't
12001  // matter whether the user app sees the old or the new data until we
12002  // return (writes going to either page is acceptable prior to return
12003  // from this function). There is no race with I/O and ProbeAndLockPages
12004  // because the PFN lock is acquired here.
12005  //
12006 
12007  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
12008 
12009 #if !defined (_X86PAE_)
12010  MiFillMemoryPte (PointerPte, NumberOfPtes, PteContents.u.Long);
12011 #else
12012 
12013  //
12014  // Note that the PAE architecture must very carefully fill these PTEs.
12015  //
12016 
12017  do {
12018  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 1);
12019  PointerPte += 1;
12020  InterlockedExchangePte (PointerPte, PteContents.u.Long);
12021  } while (PointerPte < LastPte);
12022  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (BaseAddress);
12023 
12024 #endif
12025 
12026  if (NumberOfPtes == 1) {
12027  MI_FLUSH_SINGLE_TB (BaseAddress, FALSE);
12028  }
12029  else {
12030  MI_FLUSH_PROCESS_TB (FALSE);
12031  }
12032 
12033  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
12034 
12035  UNLOCK_WS_UNSAFE (Thread, Process);
12036 
12037  MmUnlockPageableImageSection (ExPageLockHandle);
12038 
12039  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
12040 
12041 ErrorReturn:
12042 
12043  UNLOCK_ADDRESS_SPACE (Process);
12044 
12045  return Status;
12046 }
12047 
12048 
12049 PHYSICAL_ADDRESS
12050 MmGetPhysicalAddress (
12051  __in PVOID BaseAddress
12052  )
12053 
12054 /*++
12055 
12056 Routine Description:
12057 
12058  This function returns the corresponding physical address for a
12059  valid virtual address.
12060 
12061 Arguments:
12062 
12063  BaseAddress - Supplies the virtual address for which to return the
12064  physical address.
12065 
12066 Return Value:
12067 
12068  Returns the corresponding physical address.
12069 
12070 Environment:
12071 
12072  Kernel mode. Any IRQL level.
12073 
12074 --*/
12075 
12076 {
12077  PMMPTE PointerPte;
12078  PHYSICAL_ADDRESS PhysicalAddress;
12079 
12080  if (MI_IS_PHYSICAL_ADDRESS(BaseAddress)) {
12081  PhysicalAddress.QuadPart = MI_CONVERT_PHYSICAL_TO_PFN (BaseAddress);
12082  }
12083  else {
12084 
12085 #if (_MI_PAGING_LEVELS>=4)
12086  PointerPte = MiGetPxeAddress (BaseAddress);
12087  if (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 0) {
12088  KdPrint(("MM:MmGetPhysicalAddressFailed base address was %p",
12089  BaseAddress));
12090  ZERO_LARGE (PhysicalAddress);
12091  return PhysicalAddress;
12092  }
12093 #endif
12094 
12095 #if (_MI_PAGING_LEVELS>=3)
12096  PointerPte = MiGetPpeAddress (BaseAddress);
12097  if (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 0) {
12098  KdPrint(("MM:MmGetPhysicalAddressFailed base address was %p",
12099  BaseAddress));
12100  ZERO_LARGE (PhysicalAddress);
12101  return PhysicalAddress;
12102  }
12103 #endif
12104 
12105  PointerPte = MiGetPdeAddress (BaseAddress);
12106  if (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 0) {
12107  KdPrint(("MM:MmGetPhysicalAddressFailed base address was %p",
12108  BaseAddress));
12109  ZERO_LARGE (PhysicalAddress);
12110  return PhysicalAddress;
12111  }
12112 
12113  if (MI_PDE_MAPS_LARGE_PAGE (PointerPte)) {
12114  PhysicalAddress.QuadPart = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (PointerPte) +
12115  MiGetPteOffset (BaseAddress);
12116  }
12117  else {
12118  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (BaseAddress);
12119 
12120  if (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 0) {
12121  KdPrint(("MM:MmGetPhysicalAddressFailed base address was %p",
12122  BaseAddress));
12123  ZERO_LARGE (PhysicalAddress);
12124  return PhysicalAddress;
12125  }
12126  PhysicalAddress.QuadPart = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (PointerPte);
12127  }
12128  }
12129 
12130  PhysicalAddress.QuadPart = PhysicalAddress.QuadPart << PAGE_SHIFT;
12131  PhysicalAddress.LowPart += BYTE_OFFSET(BaseAddress);
12132 
12133  return PhysicalAddress;
12134 }
12135 
12136 PVOID
12137 MmGetVirtualForPhysical (
12138  __in PHYSICAL_ADDRESS PhysicalAddress
12139  )
12140 
12141 /*++
12142 
12143 Routine Description:
12144 
12145  This function returns the corresponding virtual address for a physical
12146  address whose primary virtual address is in system space.
12147 
12148 Arguments:
12149 
12150  PhysicalAddress - Supplies the physical address for which to return the
12151  virtual address.
12152 
12153 Return Value:
12154 
12155  Returns the corresponding virtual address.
12156 
12157 Environment:
12158 
12159  Kernel mode. Any IRQL level.
12160 
12161 --*/
12162 
12163 {
12164  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
12165  PMMPFN Pfn;
12166 
12167  PageFrameIndex = (PFN_NUMBER)(PhysicalAddress.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
12168 
12169  Pfn = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
12170 
12171  return (PVOID)((PCHAR)MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (Pfn->PteAddress) +
12172  BYTE_OFFSET (PhysicalAddress.LowPart));
12173 }
12174 
12175 
12176 __out_bcount(NumberOfBytes) PVOID
12177 MmAllocateNonCachedMemory (
12178  __in SIZE_T NumberOfBytes
12179  )
12180 
12181 /*++
12182 
12183 Routine Description:
12184 
12185  This function allocates a range of noncached memory in
12186  the non-paged portion of the system address space.
12187 
12188  This routine is designed to be used by a driver's initialization
12189  routine to allocate a noncached block of virtual memory for
12190  various device specific buffers.
12191 
12192 Arguments:
12193 
12194  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes to allocate.
12195 
12196 Return Value:
12197 
12198  NON-NULL - Returns a pointer (virtual address in the nonpaged portion
12199  of the system) to the allocated physically contiguous
12200  memory.
12201 
12202  NULL - The specified request could not be satisfied.
12203 
12204 Environment:
12205 
12206  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
12207 
12208 --*/
12209 
12210 {
12211  PPFN_NUMBER Page;
12212  PMMPTE PointerPte;
12213  MMPTE TempPte;
12214  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages;
12215  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
12216  PMDL Mdl;
12217  PVOID BaseAddress;
12218  PHYSICAL_ADDRESS LowAddress;
12219  PHYSICAL_ADDRESS HighAddress;
12220  PHYSICAL_ADDRESS SkipBytes;
12221  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPagesAllocated;
12222  MI_PFN_CACHE_ATTRIBUTE CacheAttribute;
12223 
12224  ASSERT (NumberOfBytes != 0);
12225 
12226 #if defined (_WIN64)
12227 
12228  //
12229  // Maximum allocation size is constrained by the MDL ByteCount field.
12230  //
12231 
12232  if (NumberOfBytes >= _4gb) {
12233  return NULL;
12234  }
12235 
12236 #endif
12237 
12238  NumberOfPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES(NumberOfBytes);
12239 
12240  //
12241  // Even though an MDL is not needed per se, it is much more convenient
12242  // to use the routine below because it checks for things like appropriate
12243  // cachability of the pages, etc. Note that the MDL returned may map
12244  // fewer pages than requested - check for this and if so, return NULL.
12245  //
12246 
12247  LowAddress.QuadPart = 0;
12248  HighAddress.QuadPart = (ULONGLONG)-1;
12249  SkipBytes.QuadPart = 0;
12250 
12251  CacheAttribute = MI_TRANSLATE_CACHETYPE (MmNonCached, FALSE);
12252 
12253  Mdl = MiAllocatePagesForMdl (LowAddress,
12254  HighAddress,
12255  SkipBytes,
12256  NumberOfBytes,
12257  CacheAttribute,
12258  0);
12259  if (Mdl == NULL) {
12260  return NULL;
12261  }
12262 
12263  BaseAddress = (PVOID)((PCHAR)Mdl->StartVa + Mdl->ByteOffset);
12264 
12265  NumberOfPagesAllocated = ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES (BaseAddress, Mdl->ByteCount);
12266 
12267  if (NumberOfPages != NumberOfPagesAllocated) {
12268  ASSERT (NumberOfPages > NumberOfPagesAllocated);
12269  MmFreePagesFromMdl (Mdl);
12270  ExFreePool (Mdl);
12271  return NULL;
12272  }
12273 
12274  //
12275  // Obtain enough virtual space to map the pages. Add an extra PTE so the
12276  // MDL can be stashed now and retrieved on release.
12277  //
12278 
12279  PointerPte = MiReserveSystemPtes ((ULONG)NumberOfPages + 1, SystemPteSpace);
12280 
12281  if (PointerPte == NULL) {
12282  MmFreePagesFromMdl (Mdl);
12283  ExFreePool (Mdl);
12284  return NULL;
12285  }
12286 
12287  *(PMDL *)PointerPte = Mdl;
12288  PointerPte += 1;
12289 
12290  BaseAddress = (PVOID)MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (PointerPte);
12291 
12292  Page = (PPFN_NUMBER)(Mdl + 1);
12293 
12294  MI_MAKE_VALID_KERNEL_PTE (TempPte,
12295  0,
12296  MM_READWRITE,
12297  PointerPte);
12298 
12299  MI_SET_PTE_DIRTY (TempPte);
12300 
12301  switch (CacheAttribute) {
12302 
12303  case MiNonCached:
12304  MI_DISABLE_CACHING (TempPte);
12305  break;
12306 
12307  case MiCached:
12308  break;
12309 
12310  case MiWriteCombined:
12311  MI_SET_PTE_WRITE_COMBINE (TempPte);
12312  break;
12313 
12314  default:
12315  ASSERT (FALSE);
12316  break;
12317  }
12318 
12319  MI_PREPARE_FOR_NONCACHED (CacheAttribute);
12320 
12321  do {
12322  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 0);
12323  PageFrameIndex = *Page;
12324 
12325  TempPte.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber = PageFrameIndex;
12326 
12327  MI_WRITE_VALID_PTE (PointerPte, TempPte);
12328 
12329  Page += 1;
12330  PointerPte += 1;
12331  NumberOfPages -= 1;
12332  } while (NumberOfPages != 0);
12333 
12334  return BaseAddress;
12335 }
12336 
12337 VOID
12338 MmFreeNonCachedMemory (
12339  __in_bcount(NumberOfBytes) PVOID BaseAddress,
12340  __in SIZE_T NumberOfBytes
12341  )
12342 
12343 /*++
12344 
12345 Routine Description:
12346 
12347  This function deallocates a range of noncached memory in
12348  the non-paged portion of the system address space.
12349 
12350 Arguments:
12351 
12352  BaseAddress - Supplies the base virtual address where the noncached
12353  memory resides.
12354 
12355  NumberOfBytes - Supplies the number of bytes allocated to the request.
12356  This must be the same number that was obtained with
12357  the MmAllocateNonCachedMemory call.
12358 
12359 Return Value:
12360 
12361  None.
12362 
12363 Environment:
12364 
12365  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
12366 
12367 --*/
12368 
12369 {
12370  PMDL Mdl;
12371  PMMPTE PointerPte;
12372  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages;
12373 #if DBG
12374  PFN_NUMBER i;
12375  PVOID StartingAddress;
12376 #endif
12377 
12378  ASSERT (NumberOfBytes != 0);
12379  ASSERT (PAGE_ALIGN (BaseAddress) == BaseAddress);
12380 
12381  NumberOfPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES(NumberOfBytes);
12382 
12383  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (BaseAddress);
12384 
12385  Mdl = *(PMDL *)(PointerPte - 1);
12386 
12387 #if DBG
12388  StartingAddress = (PVOID)((PCHAR)Mdl->StartVa + Mdl->ByteOffset);
12389 
12390  i = ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES (StartingAddress, Mdl->ByteCount);
12391 
12392  ASSERT (NumberOfPages == i);
12393 #endif
12394 
12395  MmFreePagesFromMdl (Mdl);
12396 
12397  ExFreePool (Mdl);
12398 
12399  MiReleaseSystemPtes (PointerPte - 1,
12400  (ULONG)NumberOfPages + 1,
12401  SystemPteSpace);
12402 
12403  return;
12404 }
12405 
12406 SIZE_T
12407 MmSizeOfMdl (
12408  __in_bcount_opt(Length) PVOID Base,
12409  __in SIZE_T Length
12410  )
12411 
12412 /*++
12413 
12414 Routine Description:
12415 
12416  This function returns the number of bytes required for an MDL for a
12417  given buffer and size.
12418 
12419 Arguments:
12420 
12421  Base - Supplies the base virtual address for the buffer.
12422 
12423  Length - Supplies the size of the buffer in bytes.
12424 
12425 Return Value:
12426 
12427  Returns the number of bytes required to contain the MDL.
12428 
12429 Environment:
12430 
12431  Kernel mode. Any IRQL level.
12432 
12433 --*/
12434 
12435 {
12436  return( sizeof( MDL ) +
12437  (ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES( Base, Length ) *
12438  sizeof( PFN_NUMBER ))
12439  );
12440 }
12441 
12442 
12443 PMDL
12444 MmCreateMdl (
12445  __in_opt PMDL MemoryDescriptorList,
12446  __in_bcount_opt(Length) PVOID Base,
12447  __in SIZE_T Length
12448  )
12449 
12450 /*++
12451 
12452 Routine Description:
12453 
12454  This function optionally allocates and initializes an MDL.
12455 
12456 Arguments:
12457 
12458  MemoryDescriptorList - Optionally supplies the address of the MDL
12459  to initialize. If this address is supplied as NULL
12460  an MDL is allocated from non-paged pool and
12461  initialized.
12462 
12463  Base - Supplies the base virtual address for the buffer.
12464 
12465  Length - Supplies the size of the buffer in bytes.
12466 
12467 Return Value:
12468 
12469  Returns the address of the initialized MDL.
12470 
12471 Environment:
12472 
12473  Kernel mode, IRQL of DISPATCH_LEVEL or below.
12474 
12475 --*/
12476 
12477 {
12478  SIZE_T MdlSize;
12479 
12480 #if defined (_WIN64)
12481  //
12482  // Since the Length has to fit into the MDL's ByteCount field, ensure it
12483  // doesn't wrap on 64-bit systems.
12484  //
12485 
12486  if (Length >= _4gb) {
12487  return NULL;
12488  }
12489 #endif
12490 
12491  MdlSize = MmSizeOfMdl (Base, Length);
12492 
12493  if (!ARGUMENT_PRESENT(MemoryDescriptorList)) {
12494 
12495  MemoryDescriptorList = (PMDL)ExAllocatePoolWithTag (NonPagedPool,
12496  MdlSize,
12497  'ldmM');
12498  if (MemoryDescriptorList == (PMDL)0) {
12499  return NULL;
12500  }
12501  }
12502 
12503  MmInitializeMdl (MemoryDescriptorList, Base, Length);
12504  return MemoryDescriptorList;
12505 }
12506 
12507 BOOLEAN
12508 MmSetAddressRangeModified (
12509  __in_bcount(Length) PVOID Address,
12510  __in SIZE_T Length
12511  )
12512 
12513 /*++
12514 
12515 Routine Description:
12516 
12517  This routine sets the modified bit in the PFN database for the
12518  pages that correspond to the specified address range.
12519 
12520  Note that the dirty bit in the PTE is cleared by this operation.
12521 
12522 Arguments:
12523 
12524  Address - Supplies the address of the start of the range. This
12525  range must reside within the system cache.
12526 
12527  Length - Supplies the length of the range.
12528 
12529 Return Value:
12530 
12531  TRUE if at least one PTE was dirty in the range, FALSE otherwise.
12532 
12533 Environment:
12534 
12535  Kernel mode. APC_LEVEL and below for pageable addresses,
12536  DISPATCH_LEVEL and below for non-pageable addresses.
12537 
12538 --*/
12539 
12540 {
12541  PMMPTE PointerPte;
12542  PMMPTE LastPte;
12543  PMMPFN Pfn1;
12544  MMPTE PteContents;
12545  KIRQL OldIrql;
12546  PVOID VaFlushList[MM_MAXIMUM_FLUSH_COUNT];
12547  ULONG Count;
12548  BOOLEAN Result;
12549 
12550  Count = 0;
12551  Result = FALSE;
12552 
12553  //
12554  // Loop on the copy on write case until the page is only
12555  // writable.
12556  //
12557 
12558  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (Address);
12559  LastPte = MiGetPteAddress ((PVOID)((PCHAR)Address + Length - 1));
12560 
12561  LOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
12562 
12563  do {
12564 
12565  PteContents = *PointerPte;
12566 
12567  if (PteContents.u.Hard.Valid == 1) {
12568 
12569  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PteContents.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber);
12570 
12571  MI_SET_MODIFIED (Pfn1, 1, 0x5);
12572 
12573  if ((Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Soft.Prototype == 0) &&
12574  (Pfn1->u3.e1.WriteInProgress == 0)) {
12575  MiReleasePageFileSpace (Pfn1->OriginalPte);
12576  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Soft.PageFileHigh = 0;
12577  }
12578 
12579 #ifdef NT_UP
12580  //
12581  // On uniprocessor systems no need to flush if this processor
12582  // doesn't think the PTE is dirty.
12583  //
12584 
12585  if (MI_IS_PTE_DIRTY (PteContents)) {
12586  Result = TRUE;
12587 #else //NT_UP
12588  Result |= (BOOLEAN)(MI_IS_PTE_DIRTY (PteContents));
12589 #endif //NT_UP
12590 
12591  //
12592  // Clear the write bit in the PTE so new writes can be tracked.
12593  //
12594 
12595  MI_SET_PTE_CLEAN (PteContents);
12596  MI_WRITE_VALID_PTE_NEW_PROTECTION (PointerPte, PteContents);
12597 
12598  if (Count != MM_MAXIMUM_FLUSH_COUNT) {
12599  VaFlushList[Count] = Address;
12600  Count += 1;
12601  }
12602 #ifdef NT_UP
12603  }
12604 #endif //NT_UP
12605  }
12606  PointerPte += 1;
12607  Address = (PVOID)((PCHAR)Address + PAGE_SIZE);
12608  } while (PointerPte <= LastPte);
12609 
12610  if (Count != 0) {
12611  if (Count == 1) {
12612  MI_FLUSH_SINGLE_TB (VaFlushList[0], TRUE);
12613  }
12614  else if (Count != MM_MAXIMUM_FLUSH_COUNT) {
12615  MI_FLUSH_MULTIPLE_TB (Count, &VaFlushList[0], TRUE);
12616  }
12617  else {
12618  MI_FLUSH_ENTIRE_TB (6);
12619  }
12620  }
12621  UNLOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
12622  return Result;
12623 }
12624 
12625 
12626 PVOID
12627 MiCheckForContiguousMemory (
12628  IN PVOID BaseAddress,
12629  IN PFN_NUMBER BaseAddressPages,
12630  IN PFN_NUMBER SizeInPages,
12631  IN PFN_NUMBER LowestPfn,
12632  IN PFN_NUMBER HighestPfn,
12633  IN PFN_NUMBER BoundaryPfn,
12634  IN MI_PFN_CACHE_ATTRIBUTE CacheAttribute
12635  )
12636 
12637 /*++
12638 
12639 Routine Description:
12640 
12641  This routine checks to see if the physical memory mapped
12642  by the specified BaseAddress for the specified size is
12643  contiguous and that the first page is greater than or equal to
12644  the specified LowestPfn and that the last page of the physical memory is
12645  less than or equal to the specified HighestPfn.
12646 
12647 Arguments:
12648 
12649  BaseAddress - Supplies the base address to start checking at.
12650 
12651  BaseAddressPages - Supplies the number of pages to scan from the
12652  BaseAddress.
12653 
12654  SizeInPages - Supplies the number of pages in the range.
12655 
12656  LowestPfn - Supplies lowest PFN acceptable as a physical page.
12657 
12658  HighestPfn - Supplies the highest PFN acceptable as a physical page.
12659 
12660  BoundaryPfn - Supplies the PFN multiple the allocation must
12661  not cross. 0 indicates it can cross any boundary.
12662 
12663  CacheAttribute - Supplies the type of cache mapping that will be used
12664  for the memory.
12665 
12666 Return Value:
12667 
12668  Returns the usable virtual address within the argument range that the
12669  caller should return to his caller. NULL if there is no usable address.
12670 
12671 Environment:
12672 
12673  Kernel mode, memory management internal.
12674 
12675 --*/
12676 
12677 {
12678  KIRQL OldIrql;
12679  PMMPTE PointerPte;
12680  PMMPTE LastPte;
12681  PFN_NUMBER PreviousPage;
12682  PFN_NUMBER Page;
12683  PFN_NUMBER HighestStartPage;
12684  PFN_NUMBER LastPage;
12685  PFN_NUMBER OriginalPage;
12686  PFN_NUMBER OriginalLastPage;
12687  PVOID BoundaryAllocation;
12688  PFN_NUMBER BoundaryMask;
12689  PFN_NUMBER PageCount;
12690  MMPTE PteContents;
12691 
12692  BoundaryMask = ~(BoundaryPfn - 1);
12693 
12694  if (LowestPfn > HighestPfn) {
12695  return NULL;
12696  }
12697 
12698  if (LowestPfn + SizeInPages <= LowestPfn) {
12699  return NULL;
12700  }
12701 
12702  if (LowestPfn + SizeInPages - 1 > HighestPfn) {
12703  return NULL;
12704  }
12705 
12706  if (BaseAddressPages < SizeInPages) {
12707  return NULL;
12708  }
12709 
12710  if (MI_IS_PHYSICAL_ADDRESS (BaseAddress)) {
12711 
12712  //
12713  // All physical addresses are by definition cached and therefore do
12714  // not qualify for our caller.
12715  //
12716 
12717  if (CacheAttribute != MiCached) {
12718  return NULL;
12719  }
12720 
12721  OriginalPage = MI_CONVERT_PHYSICAL_TO_PFN(BaseAddress);
12722  OriginalLastPage = OriginalPage + BaseAddressPages;
12723 
12724  Page = OriginalPage;
12725  LastPage = OriginalLastPage;
12726 
12727  //
12728  // Close the gaps, then examine the range for a fit.
12729  //
12730 
12731  if (Page < LowestPfn) {
12732  Page = LowestPfn;
12733  }
12734 
12735  if (LastPage > HighestPfn + 1) {
12736  LastPage = HighestPfn + 1;
12737  }
12738 
12739  HighestStartPage = LastPage - SizeInPages;
12740 
12741  if (Page > HighestStartPage) {
12742  return NULL;
12743  }
12744 
12745  if (BoundaryPfn != 0) {
12746  do {
12747  if (((Page ^ (Page + SizeInPages - 1)) & BoundaryMask) == 0) {
12748 
12749  //
12750  // This portion of the range meets the alignment
12751  // requirements.
12752  //
12753 
12754  break;
12755  }
12756  Page |= (BoundaryPfn - 1);
12757  Page += 1;
12758  } while (Page <= HighestStartPage);
12759 
12760  if (Page > HighestStartPage) {
12761  return NULL;
12762  }
12763  BoundaryAllocation = (PVOID)((PCHAR)BaseAddress + ((Page - OriginalPage) << PAGE_SHIFT));
12764 
12765  //
12766  // The request can be satisfied. Since specific alignment was
12767  // requested, return the fit now without getting fancy.
12768  //
12769 
12770  return BoundaryAllocation;
12771  }
12772 
12773  //
12774  // If possible return a chunk on the end to reduce fragmentation.
12775  //
12776 
12777  if (LastPage == OriginalLastPage) {
12778  return (PVOID)((PCHAR)BaseAddress + ((BaseAddressPages - SizeInPages) << PAGE_SHIFT));
12779  }
12780 
12781  //
12782  // The end chunk did not satisfy the requirements. The next best option
12783  // is to return a chunk from the beginning. Since that's where the search
12784  // began, just return the current chunk.
12785  //
12786 
12787  return (PVOID)((PCHAR)BaseAddress + ((Page - OriginalPage) << PAGE_SHIFT));
12788  }
12789 
12790  //
12791  // Check the virtual addresses for physical contiguity.
12792  //
12793 
12794  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (BaseAddress);
12795  LastPte = PointerPte + BaseAddressPages;
12796 
12797  HighestStartPage = HighestPfn + 1 - SizeInPages;
12798  PageCount = 0;
12799 
12800  //
12801  // Initializing PreviousPage is not needed for correctness
12802  // but without it the compiler cannot compile this code
12803  // W4 to check for use of uninitialized variables.
12804  //
12805 
12806  PreviousPage = 0;
12807 
12808  while (PointerPte < LastPte) {
12809 
12810  PteContents = *PointerPte;
12811  ASSERT (PteContents.u.Hard.Valid == 1);
12812  Page = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (&PteContents);
12813 
12814  //
12815  // Before starting a new run, ensure that it
12816  // can satisfy the location & boundary requirements (if any).
12817  //
12818 
12819  if (PageCount == 0) {
12820 
12821  if ((Page >= LowestPfn) &&
12822  (Page <= HighestStartPage) &&
12823  ((CacheAttribute == MiCached) || (MI_PFN_ELEMENT (Page)->u4.MustBeCached == 0))) {
12824 
12825  if (BoundaryPfn == 0) {
12826  PageCount += 1;
12827  }
12828  else if (((Page ^ (Page + SizeInPages - 1)) & BoundaryMask) == 0) {
12829  //
12830  // This run's physical address meets the alignment
12831  // requirement.
12832  //
12833 
12834  PageCount += 1;
12835  }
12836  }
12837 
12838  if (PageCount == SizeInPages) {
12839 
12840  if (CacheAttribute != MiCached) {
12841 
12842  //
12843  // Recheck the cachability while holding the PFN lock.
12844  //
12845 
12846  LOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
12847 
12848  if (MI_PFN_ELEMENT (Page)->u4.MustBeCached == 0) {
12849  PageCount = 1;
12850  }
12851  else {
12852  PageCount = 0;
12853  }
12854 
12855  UNLOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
12856  }
12857 
12858  if (PageCount != 0) {
12859 
12860  //
12861  // Success - found a single page satifying the requirements.
12862  //
12863 
12864  BaseAddress = MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (PointerPte);
12865  return BaseAddress;
12866  }
12867  }
12868 
12869  PreviousPage = Page;
12870  PointerPte += 1;
12871  continue;
12872  }
12873 
12874  if (Page != PreviousPage + 1) {
12875 
12876  //
12877  // This page is not physically contiguous. Start over.
12878  //
12879 
12880  PageCount = 0;
12881  continue;
12882  }
12883 
12884  PageCount += 1;
12885 
12886  if (PageCount == SizeInPages) {
12887 
12888  if (CacheAttribute != MiCached) {
12889 
12890  LOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
12891 
12892  do {
12893  if ((MI_PFN_ELEMENT (Page))->u4.MustBeCached == 1) {
12894  break;
12895  }
12896 
12897  Page -= 1;
12898  PageCount -= 1;
12899 
12900  } while (PageCount != 0);
12901 
12902  UNLOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
12903 
12904  if (PageCount != 0) {
12905  PageCount = 0;
12906  continue;
12907  }
12908 
12909  PageCount = SizeInPages;
12910  }
12911 
12912  //
12913  // Success - found a page range satifying the requirements.
12914  //
12915 
12916  BaseAddress = MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (PointerPte - PageCount + 1);
12917  return BaseAddress;
12918  }
12919 
12920  PreviousPage = Page;
12921  PointerPte += 1;
12922  }
12923 
12924  return NULL;
12925 }
12926 
12927 
12928 VOID
12929 MmLockPagableSectionByHandle (
12930  __in PVOID ImageSectionHandle
12931  )
12932 {
12933  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle ( ImageSectionHandle );
12934 }
12935 
12936 VOID
12937 MmLockPageableSectionByHandle (
12938  __in PVOID ImageSectionHandle
12939  )
12940 
12941 
12942 /*++
12943 
12944 Routine Description:
12945 
12946  This routine checks to see if the specified pages are resident in
12947  the process's working set and if so the reference count for the
12948  page is incremented. The allows the virtual address to be accessed
12949  without getting a hard page fault (have to go to the disk... except
12950  for extremely rare case when the page table page is removed from the
12951  working set and migrates to the disk.
12952 
12953  If the virtual address is that of the system wide global "cache" the
12954  virtual address of the "locked" pages is always guaranteed to
12955  be valid.
12956 
12957  NOTE: This routine is not to be used for general locking of user
12958  addresses - use MmProbeAndLockPages. This routine is intended for
12959  well behaved system code like the file system caches which allocates
12960  virtual addresses for mapping files AND guarantees that the mapping
12961  will not be modified (deleted or changed) while the pages are locked.
12962 
12963 Arguments:
12964 
12965  ImageSectionHandle - Supplies the value returned by a previous call
12966  to MmLockPageableDataSection. This is a pointer to
12967  the section header for the image.
12968 
12969 Return Value:
12970 
12971  None.
12972 
12973 Environment:
12974 
12975  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
12976 
12977 --*/
12978 
12979 {
12980  ULONG EntryCount;
12981  ULONG OriginalCount;
12982  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
12983  PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER NtSection;
12984  PVOID BaseAddress;
12985  ULONG SizeToLock;
12986  PMMPTE PointerPte;
12987  PMMPTE LastPte;
12988  PLONG SectionLockCountPointer;
12989 
12990  if (MI_IS_PHYSICAL_ADDRESS(ImageSectionHandle)) {
12991 
12992  //
12993  // No need to lock physical addresses.
12994  //
12995 
12996  return;
12997  }
12998 
12999  NtSection = (PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER)ImageSectionHandle;
13000 
13001  BaseAddress = SECTION_BASE_ADDRESS(NtSection);
13002  SectionLockCountPointer = SECTION_LOCK_COUNT_POINTER (NtSection);
13003 
13004  ASSERT (!MI_IS_SYSTEM_CACHE_ADDRESS(BaseAddress));
13005 
13006  //
13007  // The address must be within the system space.
13008  //
13009 
13010  ASSERT (BaseAddress >= MmSystemRangeStart);
13011 
13012  SizeToLock = NtSection->SizeOfRawData;
13013 
13014  //
13015  // Generally, SizeOfRawData is larger than VirtualSize for each
13016  // section because it includes the padding to get to the subsection
13017  // alignment boundary. However, if the image is linked with
13018  // subsection alignment == native page alignment, the linker will
13019  // have VirtualSize be much larger than SizeOfRawData because it
13020  // will account for all the bss.
13021  //
13022 
13023  if (SizeToLock < NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize) {
13024  SizeToLock = NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize;
13025  }
13026 
13027  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress(BaseAddress);
13028  LastPte = MiGetPteAddress((PCHAR)BaseAddress + SizeToLock - 1);
13029 
13030  ASSERT (SizeToLock != 0);
13031 
13032  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
13033 
13034  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13035 
13036  //
13037  // The lock count values have the following meanings :
13038  //
13039  // Value of 0 means unlocked.
13040  // Value of 1 means lock in progress by another thread.
13041  // Value of 2 or more means locked.
13042  //
13043  // If the value is 1, this thread must block until the other thread's
13044  // lock operation is complete.
13045  //
13046 
13047  do {
13048  EntryCount = *SectionLockCountPointer;
13049 
13050  if (EntryCount != 1) {
13051 
13052  OriginalCount = InterlockedCompareExchange (SectionLockCountPointer,
13053  EntryCount + 1,
13054  EntryCount);
13055 
13056  if (OriginalCount == EntryCount) {
13057 
13058  //
13059  // Success - this is the first thread to update.
13060  //
13061 
13062  ASSERT (OriginalCount != 1);
13063  break;
13064  }
13065 
13066  //
13067  // Another thread updated the count before this thread's attempt
13068  // so it's time to start over.
13069  //
13070  }
13071  else {
13072 
13073  //
13074  // A lock is in progress, wait for it to finish. This should be
13075  // generally rare, and even in this case, the pulse will usually
13076  // wake us. A timeout is used so that the wait and the pulse do
13077  // not need to be interlocked.
13078  //
13079 
13080  InterlockedIncrement (&MmCollidedLockWait);
13081 
13082  KeWaitForSingleObject (&MmCollidedLockEvent,
13083  WrVirtualMemory,
13084  KernelMode,
13085  FALSE,
13086  (PLARGE_INTEGER)&MmShortTime);
13087 
13088  InterlockedDecrement (&MmCollidedLockWait);
13089  }
13090 
13091  } while (TRUE);
13092 
13093  if (OriginalCount >= 2) {
13094 
13095  //
13096  // Already locked, just return.
13097  //
13098 
13099  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13100  return;
13101  }
13102 
13103  ASSERT (OriginalCount == 0);
13104  ASSERT (*SectionLockCountPointer == 1);
13105 
13106  //
13107  // Value was 0 when the lock was obtained. It is now 1 indicating
13108  // a lock is in progress.
13109  //
13110 
13111  MiLockCode (PointerPte, LastPte, MM_LOCK_BY_REFCOUNT);
13112 
13113  //
13114  // Set lock count to 2 (it was 1 when this started) and check
13115  // to see if any other threads tried to lock while this was happening.
13116  //
13117 
13118  ASSERT (*SectionLockCountPointer == 1);
13119  OriginalCount = InterlockedIncrement (SectionLockCountPointer);
13120  ASSERT (OriginalCount >= 2);
13121 
13122  if (MmCollidedLockWait != 0) {
13123  KePulseEvent (&MmCollidedLockEvent, 0, FALSE);
13124  }
13125 
13126  //
13127  // Enable user APCs now that the pulse has occurred. They had to be
13128  // blocked to prevent any suspensions of this thread as that would
13129  // stop all waiters indefinitely.
13130  //
13131 
13132  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13133 
13134  return;
13135 }
13136 
13137 
13138 VOID
13139 MiLockCode (
13140  IN PMMPTE FirstPte,
13141  IN PMMPTE LastPte,
13142  IN ULONG LockType
13143  )
13144 
13145 /*++
13146 
13147 Routine Description:
13148 
13149  This routine checks to see if the specified pages are resident in
13150  the process's working set and if so the reference count for the
13151  page is incremented. This allows the virtual address to be accessed
13152  without getting a hard page fault (have to go to the disk...) except
13153  for the extremely rare case when the page table page is removed from the
13154  working set and migrates to the disk.
13155 
13156  If the virtual address is that of the system wide global "cache", the
13157  virtual address of the "locked" pages is always guaranteed to
13158  be valid.
13159 
13160  NOTE: This routine is not to be used for general locking of user
13161  addresses - use MmProbeAndLockPages. This routine is intended for
13162  well behaved system code like the file system caches which allocates
13163  virtual addresses for mapping files AND guarantees that the mapping
13164  will not be modified (deleted or changed) while the pages are locked.
13165 
13166 Arguments:
13167 
13168  FirstPte - Supplies the base address to begin locking.
13169 
13170  LastPte - The last PTE to lock.
13171 
13172  LockType - Supplies either MM_LOCK_BY_REFCOUNT or MM_LOCK_NONPAGE.
13173  LOCK_BY_REFCOUNT increments the reference count to keep
13174  the page in memory, LOCK_NONPAGE removes the page from
13175  the working set so it's locked just like nonpaged pool.
13176 
13177 Return Value:
13178 
13179  None.
13180 
13181 Environment:
13182 
13183  Kernel mode.
13184 
13185 --*/
13186 
13187 {
13188  PMMPFN Pfn1;
13189  PMMPTE PointerPte;
13190  MMPTE TempPte;
13191  MMPTE PteContents;
13192  WSLE_NUMBER WorkingSetIndex;
13193  WSLE_NUMBER SwapEntry;
13194  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
13195  KIRQL OldIrql;
13196  LOGICAL SessionSpace;
13197  PMMWSL WorkingSetList;
13198  PMMSUPPORT Vm;
13199  PETHREAD CurrentThread;
13200 
13201  ASSERT (!MI_IS_PHYSICAL_ADDRESS(MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte(FirstPte)));
13202  PointerPte = FirstPte;
13203 
13204  CurrentThread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
13205 
13206  SessionSpace = MI_IS_SESSION_IMAGE_ADDRESS (MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte(FirstPte));
13207 
13208  if (SessionSpace == TRUE) {
13209  Vm = &MmSessionSpace->GlobalVirtualAddress->Vm;
13210  WorkingSetList = MmSessionSpace->Vm.VmWorkingSetList;
13211 
13212  //
13213  // Session space is never locked by refcount.
13214  //
13215 
13216  ASSERT (LockType != MM_LOCK_BY_REFCOUNT);
13217  }
13218  else {
13219 
13220  Vm = &MmSystemCacheWs;
13221  WorkingSetList = NULL;
13222  }
13223 
13224  LOCK_WORKING_SET (CurrentThread, Vm);
13225 
13226  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13227 
13228  do {
13229 
13230  PteContents = *PointerPte;
13231  ASSERT (PteContents.u.Long != 0);
13232  if (PteContents.u.Hard.Valid == 1) {
13233 
13234  //
13235  // This address is already in the system (or session) working set.
13236  //
13237 
13238  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PteContents.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber);
13239 
13240  //
13241  // Up the reference count so the page cannot be released.
13242  //
13243 
13244  MI_ADD_LOCKED_PAGE_CHARGE (Pfn1);
13245 
13246  if (LockType != MM_LOCK_BY_REFCOUNT) {
13247 
13248  //
13249  // If the page is in the system working set, remove it.
13250  // The system working set lock MUST be owned to check to
13251  // see if this page is in the working set or not. This
13252  // is because the pager may have just released the PFN lock,
13253  // acquired the system lock and is now trying to add the
13254  // page to the system working set.
13255  //
13256  // If the page is in the SESSION working set, it cannot be
13257  // removed as all these pages are carefully accounted for.
13258  // Instead move it to the locked portion of the working set
13259  // if it is not there already.
13260  //
13261 
13262  if (Pfn1->u1.WsIndex != 0) {
13263 
13264  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13265 
13266  if (SessionSpace == TRUE) {
13267 
13268  WorkingSetIndex = MiLocateWsle (
13269  MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte(PointerPte),
13270  WorkingSetList,
13271  Pfn1->u1.WsIndex,
13272  FALSE);
13273 
13274  if (WorkingSetIndex >= WorkingSetList->FirstDynamic) {
13275 
13276  SwapEntry = WorkingSetList->FirstDynamic;
13277 
13278  if (WorkingSetIndex != WorkingSetList->FirstDynamic) {
13279 
13280  //
13281  // Swap this entry with the one at first
13282  // dynamic. Note that the working set index
13283  // in the PTE is updated here as well.
13284  //
13285 
13286  MiSwapWslEntries (WorkingSetIndex,
13287  SwapEntry,
13288  Vm,
13289  FALSE);
13290  }
13291 
13292  WorkingSetList->FirstDynamic += 1;
13293 
13294  //
13295  // Indicate that the page is now locked.
13296  //
13297 
13298  MmSessionSpace->Wsle[SwapEntry].u1.e1.LockedInWs = 1;
13299  MM_BUMP_SESS_COUNTER (MM_DBG_SESSION_NP_LOCK_CODE2, 1);
13300  InterlockedIncrementSizeT (&MmSessionSpace->NonPageablePages);
13301  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13302  Pfn1->u1.WsIndex = SwapEntry;
13303 
13304  //
13305  // Adjust available pages as this page is now not
13306  // in any working set, just like a non-paged pool
13307  // page.
13308  //
13309 
13310  MI_DECREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (1, MM_RESAVAIL_ALLOCATE_LOCK_CODE1);
13311 
13312  if (Pfn1->u3.e1.PrototypePte == 0) {
13313  InterlockedDecrement (&MmTotalSystemDriverPages);
13314  }
13315  }
13316  else {
13317  ASSERT (MmSessionSpace->Wsle[WorkingSetIndex].u1.e1.LockedInWs == 1);
13318  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13319  }
13320  }
13321  else {
13322  MiRemoveWsle (Pfn1->u1.WsIndex, MmSystemCacheWorkingSetList);
13323  MiReleaseWsle (Pfn1->u1.WsIndex, &MmSystemCacheWs);
13324 
13325  MI_SET_PTE_IN_WORKING_SET (PointerPte, 0);
13326  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13327  MI_ZERO_WSINDEX (Pfn1);
13328 
13329  //
13330  // Adjust available pages as this page is now not in any
13331  // working set, just like a non-paged pool page.
13332  //
13333 
13334  MI_DECREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (1, MM_RESAVAIL_ALLOCATE_LOCK_CODE2);
13335 
13336  if (Pfn1->u3.e1.PrototypePte == 0) {
13337  InterlockedDecrement (&MmTotalSystemDriverPages);
13338  }
13339  }
13340 
13341  }
13342  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount > 1);
13343  MI_REMOVE_LOCKED_PAGE_CHARGE_AND_DECREF (Pfn1);
13344  }
13345  }
13346  else if (PteContents.u.Soft.Prototype == 1) {
13347 
13348  //
13349  // Page is not in memory and it is a prototype.
13350  //
13351 
13352  MiMakeSystemAddressValidPfnSystemWs (
13353  MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte(PointerPte), OldIrql);
13354 
13355  continue;
13356  }
13357  else if (PteContents.u.Soft.Transition == 1) {
13358 
13359  PageFrameIndex = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_TRANSITION_PTE (&PteContents);
13360 
13361  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
13362  if ((Pfn1->u3.e1.ReadInProgress) ||
13363  (Pfn1->u4.InPageError)) {
13364 
13365  //
13366  // Page read is ongoing, force a collided fault.
13367  //
13368 
13369  MiMakeSystemAddressValidPfnSystemWs (
13370  MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte(PointerPte), OldIrql);
13371 
13372  continue;
13373  }
13374 
13375  //
13376  // Paged pool is trimmed without regard to sharecounts.
13377  // This means a paged pool PTE can be in transition while
13378  // the page is still marked active.
13379  //
13380 
13381  if (Pfn1->u3.e1.PageLocation == ActiveAndValid) {
13382 
13383  ASSERT (((Pfn1->PteAddress >= MiGetPteAddress(MmPagedPoolStart)) &&
13384  (Pfn1->PteAddress <= MiGetPteAddress(MmPagedPoolEnd))) ||
13385  ((Pfn1->PteAddress >= MiGetPteAddress(MmSpecialPoolStart)) &&
13386  (Pfn1->PteAddress <= MiGetPteAddress(MmSpecialPoolEnd))));
13387 
13388  //
13389  // Don't increment the valid PTE count for the
13390  // paged pool page.
13391  //
13392 
13393  ASSERT (Pfn1->u2.ShareCount != 0);
13394  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount != 0);
13395  Pfn1->u2.ShareCount += 1;
13396  }
13397  else {
13398 
13399  if (MmAvailablePages == 0) {
13400 
13401  //
13402  // This can only happen if the system is utilizing
13403  // a hardware compression cache. This ensures that
13404  // only a safe amount of the compressed virtual cache
13405  // is directly mapped so that if the hardware gets
13406  // into trouble, we can bail it out.
13407  //
13408  // Just unlock everything here to give the compression
13409  // reaper a chance to ravage pages and then retry.
13410  //
13411 
13412  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13413 
13414  UNLOCK_WORKING_SET (CurrentThread, Vm);
13415 
13416  LOCK_WORKING_SET (CurrentThread, Vm);
13417 
13418  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13419 
13420  continue;
13421  }
13422 
13423  MiUnlinkPageFromList (Pfn1);
13424 
13425  //
13426  // Increment the reference count and set the share count to 1.
13427  // Note the reference count may be 1 already if a modified page
13428  // write is underway. The systemwide locked page charges
13429  // are correct in either case and nothing needs to be done
13430  // just yet.
13431  //
13432 
13433  InterlockedIncrement16 ((PSHORT)&Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount);
13434  Pfn1->u2.ShareCount = 1;
13435  }
13436 
13437  Pfn1->u3.e1.PageLocation = ActiveAndValid;
13438 
13439  MI_MAKE_VALID_PTE (TempPte,
13440  PageFrameIndex,
13441  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Soft.Protection,
13442  PointerPte);
13443 
13444  MI_WRITE_VALID_PTE (PointerPte, TempPte);
13445 
13446  //
13447  // Increment the reference count one for putting it the
13448  // working set list and one for locking it for I/O.
13449  //
13450 
13451  if (LockType == MM_LOCK_BY_REFCOUNT) {
13452 
13453  //
13454  // Lock the page in the working set by upping the
13455  // reference count.
13456  //
13457 
13458  MI_ADD_LOCKED_PAGE_CHARGE (Pfn1);
13459 
13460  Pfn1->u1.Event = NULL;
13461 
13462  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13463 
13464  WorkingSetIndex = MiAllocateWsle (Vm,
13465  PointerPte,
13466  Pfn1,
13467  0);
13468 
13469  if (WorkingSetIndex == 0) {
13470 
13471  //
13472  // No working set entry was available. Another (broken
13473  // or malicious thread) may have already written to this
13474  // page since the PTE was made valid. So trim the
13475  // page instead of discarding it.
13476  //
13477  // Note the page cannot be a prototype because the
13478  // PTE was transition above.
13479  //
13480 
13481  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e1.PrototypePte == 0);
13482 
13483  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13484 
13485  //
13486  // Undo the reference count & locked page charge (if any).
13487  //
13488 
13489  MI_REMOVE_LOCKED_PAGE_CHARGE_AND_DECREF (Pfn1);
13490 
13491  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13492 
13493  MiTrimPte (MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (PointerPte),
13494  PointerPte,
13495  Pfn1,
13496  NULL,
13497  ZeroPte);
13498 
13499  //
13500  // Release all locks so that other threads (like the
13501  // working set trimmer) can try to freely make memory.
13502  //
13503 
13504  UNLOCK_WORKING_SET (CurrentThread, Vm);
13505 
13506  KeDelayExecutionThread (KernelMode,
13507  FALSE,
13508  (PLARGE_INTEGER)&Mm30Milliseconds);
13509 
13510  LOCK_WORKING_SET (CurrentThread, Vm);
13511 
13512  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13513 
13514  //
13515  // Retry the same page now.
13516  //
13517 
13518  continue;
13519  }
13520 
13521  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13522  }
13523  else {
13524 
13525  //
13526  // The wsindex field must be zero because the
13527  // page is not in the system (or session) working set.
13528  //
13529 
13530  ASSERT (Pfn1->u1.WsIndex == 0);
13531 
13532  //
13533  // Adjust available pages as this page is now not in any
13534  // working set, just like a non-paged pool page. On entry
13535  // this page was in transition so it was part of the
13536  // available pages by definition.
13537  //
13538 
13539  MI_DECREMENT_RESIDENT_AVAILABLE (1, MM_RESAVAIL_ALLOCATE_LOCK_CODE3);
13540 
13541  if (Pfn1->u3.e1.PrototypePte == 0) {
13542  InterlockedDecrement (&MmTotalSystemDriverPages);
13543  }
13544  if (SessionSpace == TRUE) {
13545  MM_BUMP_SESS_COUNTER (MM_DBG_SESSION_NP_LOCK_CODE1, 1);
13546  InterlockedIncrementSizeT (&MmSessionSpace->NonPageablePages);
13547  }
13548  }
13549  }
13550  else {
13551 
13552  //
13553  // Page is not in memory.
13554  //
13555 
13556  MiMakeSystemAddressValidPfnSystemWs (
13557  MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte(PointerPte), OldIrql);
13558 
13559  continue;
13560  }
13561 
13562  PointerPte += 1;
13563  } while (PointerPte <= LastPte);
13564 
13565  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
13566 
13567  UNLOCK_WORKING_SET (CurrentThread, Vm);
13568 
13569  return;
13570 }
13571 
13572 
13573 NTSTATUS
13574 MmGetSectionRange (
13575  IN PVOID AddressWithinSection,
13576  OUT PVOID *StartingSectionAddress,
13577  OUT PULONG SizeofSection
13578  )
13579 {
13580  ULONG Span;
13581  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
13582  PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY DataTableEntry;
13583  ULONG i;
13584  PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS NtHeaders;
13585  PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER NtSection;
13586  NTSTATUS Status;
13587  ULONG_PTR Rva;
13588 
13589  PAGED_CODE();
13590 
13591  //
13592  // Search the loaded module list for the data table entry that describes
13593  // the DLL that was just unloaded. It is possible that an entry is not in
13594  // the list if a failure occurred at a point in loading the DLL just before
13595  // the data table entry was generated.
13596  //
13597 
13598  Status = STATUS_NOT_FOUND;
13599 
13600  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
13601  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13602  ExAcquireResourceSharedLite (&PsLoadedModuleResource, TRUE);
13603 
13604  DataTableEntry = MiLookupDataTableEntry (AddressWithinSection, TRUE);
13605  if (DataTableEntry) {
13606 
13607  Rva = (ULONG_PTR)((PUCHAR)AddressWithinSection - (ULONG_PTR)DataTableEntry->DllBase);
13608 
13609  NtHeaders = (PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS) RtlImageNtHeader (DataTableEntry->DllBase);
13610  if (NtHeaders == NULL) {
13611  Status = STATUS_NOT_FOUND;
13612  goto Finished;
13613  }
13614 
13615  NtSection = (PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER)((PCHAR)NtHeaders +
13616  sizeof(ULONG) +
13617  sizeof(IMAGE_FILE_HEADER) +
13618  NtHeaders->FileHeader.SizeOfOptionalHeader
13619  );
13620 
13621  for (i = 0; i < NtHeaders->FileHeader.NumberOfSections; i += 1) {
13622 
13623  //
13624  // Generally, SizeOfRawData is larger than VirtualSize for each
13625  // section because it includes the padding to get to the subsection
13626  // alignment boundary. However if the image is linked with
13627  // subsection alignment == native page alignment, the linker will
13628  // have VirtualSize be much larger than SizeOfRawData because it
13629  // will account for all the bss.
13630  //
13631 
13632  Span = NtSection->SizeOfRawData;
13633 
13634  if (Span < NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize) {
13635  Span = NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize;
13636  }
13637 
13638  if ((Rva >= NtSection->VirtualAddress) &&
13639  (Rva < NtSection->VirtualAddress + Span)) {
13640 
13641  //
13642  // Found it.
13643  //
13644 
13645  *StartingSectionAddress = (PVOID)
13646  ((PCHAR) DataTableEntry->DllBase + NtSection->VirtualAddress);
13647  *SizeofSection = Span;
13648  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
13649  break;
13650  }
13651 
13652  NtSection += 1;
13653  }
13654  }
13655 
13656 Finished:
13657 
13658  ExReleaseResourceLite (&PsLoadedModuleResource);
13659  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13660  return Status;
13661 }
13662 
13663 
13664 PVOID
13665 MmLockPageableDataSection (
13666  __in PVOID AddressWithinSection
13667  )
13668 
13669 /*++
13670 
13671 Routine Description:
13672 
13673  This functions locks the entire section that contains the specified
13674  section in memory. This allows pageable code to be brought into
13675  memory and to be used as if the code was not really pageable. This
13676  should not be done with a high degree of frequency.
13677 
13678 Arguments:
13679 
13680  AddressWithinSection - Supplies the address of a function
13681  contained within a section that should be brought in and locked
13682  in memory.
13683 
13684 Return Value:
13685 
13686  This function returns a value to be used in a subsequent call to
13687  MmUnlockPageableImageSection.
13688 
13689 --*/
13690 
13691 {
13692  ULONG Span;
13693  PLONG SectionLockCountPointer;
13694  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
13695  PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY DataTableEntry;
13696  ULONG i;
13697  PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS NtHeaders;
13698  PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER NtSection;
13699  PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER FoundSection;
13700  ULONG_PTR Rva;
13701 
13702  PAGED_CODE();
13703 
13704  if (MI_IS_PHYSICAL_ADDRESS(AddressWithinSection)) {
13705 
13706  //
13707  // Physical address, just return that as the handle.
13708  //
13709 
13710  return AddressWithinSection;
13711  }
13712 
13713  //
13714  // Search the loaded module list for the data table entry that describes
13715  // the DLL that was just unloaded. It is possible that an entry is not in
13716  // the list if a failure occurred at a point in loading the DLL just before
13717  // the data table entry was generated.
13718  //
13719 
13720  FoundSection = NULL;
13721 
13722  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
13723  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13724  ExAcquireResourceSharedLite (&PsLoadedModuleResource, TRUE);
13725 
13726  DataTableEntry = MiLookupDataTableEntry (AddressWithinSection, TRUE);
13727 
13728  Rva = (ULONG_PTR)((PUCHAR)AddressWithinSection - (ULONG_PTR)DataTableEntry->DllBase);
13729 
13730  NtHeaders = (PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS) RtlImageNtHeader (DataTableEntry->DllBase);
13731 
13732  if (NtHeaders == NULL) {
13733 
13734  //
13735  // This is a firmware entry - no one should be trying to lock these.
13736  //
13737 
13738  KeBugCheckEx (MEMORY_MANAGEMENT,
13739  0x1234,
13740  (ULONG_PTR)AddressWithinSection,
13741  1,
13742  0);
13743  }
13744 
13745  NtSection = (PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER)((ULONG_PTR)NtHeaders +
13746  sizeof(ULONG) +
13747  sizeof(IMAGE_FILE_HEADER) +
13748  NtHeaders->FileHeader.SizeOfOptionalHeader
13749  );
13750 
13751  for (i = 0; i < NtHeaders->FileHeader.NumberOfSections; i += 1) {
13752 
13753  //
13754  // Generally, SizeOfRawData is larger than VirtualSize for each
13755  // section because it includes the padding to get to the subsection
13756  // alignment boundary. However, if the image is linked with
13757  // subsection alignment == native page alignment, the linker will
13758  // have VirtualSize be much larger than SizeOfRawData because it
13759  // will account for all the bss.
13760  //
13761 
13762  Span = NtSection->SizeOfRawData;
13763 
13764  if (Span < NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize) {
13765  Span = NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize;
13766  }
13767 
13768  if ((Rva >= NtSection->VirtualAddress) &&
13769  (Rva < NtSection->VirtualAddress + Span)) {
13770 
13771  FoundSection = NtSection;
13772 
13773  if (SECTION_BASE_ADDRESS(NtSection) != ((PUCHAR)DataTableEntry->DllBase +
13774  NtSection->VirtualAddress)) {
13775 
13776  //
13777  // Overwrite the PointerToRelocations field (and on Win64, the
13778  // PointerToLinenumbers field also) so that it contains
13779  // the Va of this section.
13780  //
13781  // NumberOfRelocations & NumberOfLinenumbers contains
13782  // the Lock Count for the section.
13783  //
13784 
13785  SECTION_BASE_ADDRESS(NtSection) = ((PUCHAR)DataTableEntry->DllBase +
13786  NtSection->VirtualAddress);
13787 
13788  SectionLockCountPointer = SECTION_LOCK_COUNT_POINTER (NtSection);
13789  *SectionLockCountPointer = 0;
13790  }
13791 
13792  //
13793  // Now lock in the code.
13794  //
13795 
13796  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle ((PVOID)NtSection);
13797 
13798  break;
13799  }
13800  NtSection += 1;
13801  }
13802 
13803  ExReleaseResourceLite (&PsLoadedModuleResource);
13804  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13805  if (!FoundSection) {
13806  KeBugCheckEx (MEMORY_MANAGEMENT,
13807  0x1234,
13808  (ULONG_PTR)AddressWithinSection,
13809  0,
13810  0);
13811  }
13812  return (PVOID)FoundSection;
13813 }
13814 
13815 
13816 PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY
13817 MiLookupDataTableEntry (
13818  IN PVOID AddressWithinSection,
13819  IN ULONG ResourceHeld
13820  )
13821 
13822 /*++
13823 
13824 Routine Description:
13825 
13826  This functions locates the data table entry that maps the specified address.
13827 
13828 Arguments:
13829 
13830  AddressWithinSection - Supplies the address of a function contained
13831  within the desired module.
13832 
13833  ResourceHeld - Supplies TRUE if the loaded module resource is already held,
13834  FALSE if not.
13835 
13836 Return Value:
13837 
13838  The address of the loaded module list data table entry that maps the
13839  argument address.
13840 
13841 --*/
13842 
13843 {
13844  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
13845  PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY DataTableEntry;
13846  PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY FoundEntry;
13847  PLIST_ENTRY NextEntry;
13848 
13849  PAGED_CODE();
13850 
13851  FoundEntry = NULL;
13852 
13853  //
13854  // Search the loaded module list for the data table entry that describes
13855  // the DLL that was just unloaded. It is possible that an entry is not in
13856  // the list if a failure occurred at a point in loading the DLL just before
13857  // the data table entry was generated.
13858  //
13859 
13860  if (!ResourceHeld) {
13861  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
13862  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13863  ExAcquireResourceSharedLite (&PsLoadedModuleResource, TRUE);
13864  }
13865  else {
13866  CurrentThread = NULL;
13867  }
13868 
13869  NextEntry = PsLoadedModuleList.Flink;
13870  ASSERT (NextEntry != NULL);
13871 
13872  do {
13873 
13874  DataTableEntry = CONTAINING_RECORD(NextEntry,
13875  KLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY,
13876  InLoadOrderLinks);
13877 
13878  //
13879  // Locate the loaded module that contains this address.
13880  //
13881 
13882  if ( AddressWithinSection >= DataTableEntry->DllBase &&
13883  AddressWithinSection < (PVOID)((PUCHAR)DataTableEntry->DllBase+DataTableEntry->SizeOfImage) ) {
13884 
13885  FoundEntry = DataTableEntry;
13886  break;
13887  }
13888 
13889  NextEntry = NextEntry->Flink;
13890  } while (NextEntry != &PsLoadedModuleList);
13891 
13892  if (CurrentThread != NULL) {
13893  ExReleaseResourceLite (&PsLoadedModuleResource);
13894  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13895  }
13896  return FoundEntry;
13897 }
13898 
13899 VOID
13900 MmUnlockPagableImageSection (
13901  __in PVOID ImageSectionHandle
13902  )
13903 {
13904  MmUnlockPageableImageSection ( ImageSectionHandle );
13905 }
13906 
13907 VOID
13908 MmUnlockPageableImageSection (
13909  __in PVOID ImageSectionHandle
13910  )
13911 
13912 /*++
13913 
13914 Routine Description:
13915 
13916  This function unlocks from memory, the pages locked by a preceding call to
13917  MmLockPageableDataSection.
13918 
13919 Arguments:
13920 
13921  ImageSectionHandle - Supplies the value returned by a previous call
13922  to MmLockPageableDataSection.
13923 
13924 Return Value:
13925 
13926  None.
13927 
13928 --*/
13929 
13930 {
13931  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
13932  PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER NtSection;
13933  PMMPTE PointerPte;
13934  PMMPTE LastPte;
13935  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
13936  PMMPFN Pfn1;
13937  KIRQL OldIrql;
13938  PVOID BaseAddress;
13939  ULONG SizeToUnlock;
13940  ULONG Count;
13941  PLONG SectionLockCountPointer;
13942 
13943  if (MI_IS_PHYSICAL_ADDRESS(ImageSectionHandle)) {
13944 
13945  //
13946  // No need to unlock physical addresses.
13947  //
13948 
13949  return;
13950  }
13951 
13952  NtSection = (PIMAGE_SECTION_HEADER)ImageSectionHandle;
13953 
13954  //
13955  // Address must be in the system working set.
13956  //
13957 
13958  BaseAddress = SECTION_BASE_ADDRESS(NtSection);
13959  SectionLockCountPointer = SECTION_LOCK_COUNT_POINTER (NtSection);
13960  SizeToUnlock = NtSection->SizeOfRawData;
13961 
13962  //
13963  // Generally, SizeOfRawData is larger than VirtualSize for each
13964  // section because it includes the padding to get to the subsection
13965  // alignment boundary. However, if the image is linked with
13966  // subsection alignment == native page alignment, the linker will
13967  // have VirtualSize be much larger than SizeOfRawData because it
13968  // will account for all the bss.
13969  //
13970 
13971  if (SizeToUnlock < NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize) {
13972  SizeToUnlock = NtSection->Misc.VirtualSize;
13973  }
13974 
13975  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress(BaseAddress);
13976  LastPte = MiGetPteAddress((PCHAR)BaseAddress + SizeToUnlock - 1);
13977 
13978  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
13979 
13980  //
13981  // Block user APCs as the initial decrement below could push the count to 1.
13982  // This puts this thread into the critical path that must finish as all
13983  // other threads trying to lock the section will be waiting for this thread.
13984  // Entering a critical region here ensures that a suspend cannot stop us.
13985  //
13986 
13987  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
13988 
13989  Count = InterlockedDecrement (SectionLockCountPointer);
13990 
13991  if (Count < 1) {
13992  KeBugCheckEx (MEMORY_MANAGEMENT,
13993  0x1010,
13994  (ULONG_PTR)BaseAddress,
13995  (ULONG_PTR)NtSection,
13996  *SectionLockCountPointer);
13997  }
13998 
13999  if (Count != 1) {
14000  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
14001  return;
14002  }
14003 
14004  LOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
14005 
14006  do {
14007  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 1);
14008 
14009  PageFrameIndex = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (PointerPte);
14010  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
14011 
14012  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount > 1);
14013 
14014  MI_REMOVE_LOCKED_PAGE_CHARGE_AND_DECREF (Pfn1);
14015 
14016  PointerPte += 1;
14017 
14018  } while (PointerPte <= LastPte);
14019 
14020  UNLOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
14021 
14022  ASSERT (*SectionLockCountPointer == 1);
14023  Count = InterlockedDecrement (SectionLockCountPointer);
14024  ASSERT (Count == 0);
14025 
14026  if (MmCollidedLockWait != 0) {
14027  KePulseEvent (&MmCollidedLockEvent, 0, FALSE);
14028  }
14029 
14030  //
14031  // Enable user APCs now that the pulse has occurred. They had to be
14032  // blocked to prevent any suspensions of this thread as that would
14033  // stop all waiters indefinitely.
14034  //
14035 
14036  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
14037 
14038  return;
14039 }
14040 
14041 
14042 BOOLEAN
14043 MmIsRecursiveIoFault (
14044  VOID
14045  )
14046 
14047 /*++
14048 
14049 Routine Description:
14050 
14051  This function examines the thread's page fault clustering information
14052  and determines if the current page fault is occurring during an I/O
14053  operation.
14054 
14055 Arguments:
14056 
14057  None.
14058 
14059 Return Value:
14060 
14061  Returns TRUE if the fault is occurring during an I/O operation,
14062  FALSE otherwise.
14063 
14064 --*/
14065 
14066 {
14067  PETHREAD Thread;
14068 
14069  Thread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
14070 
14071  return (BOOLEAN)(Thread->DisablePageFaultClustering |
14072  Thread->ForwardClusterOnly);
14073 }
14074 
14075 
14076 VOID
14077 MmMapMemoryDumpMdl (
14078  __inout PMDL MemoryDumpMdl
14079  )
14080 
14081 /*++
14082 
14083 Routine Description:
14084 
14085  For use by crash dump routine ONLY. Maps an MDL into a fixed
14086  portion of the address space. Only 1 MDL can be mapped at a
14087  time.
14088 
14089 Arguments:
14090 
14091  MemoryDumpMdl - Supplies the MDL to map.
14092 
14093 Return Value:
14094 
14095  None, fields in MDL updated.
14096 
14097 --*/
14098 
14099 {
14100  PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages;
14101  PMMPTE PointerPte;
14102  PCHAR BaseVa;
14103  MMPTE TempPte;
14104  PMMPFN Pfn1;
14105  PPFN_NUMBER Page;
14106 
14107  NumberOfPages = BYTES_TO_PAGES (MemoryDumpMdl->ByteCount + MemoryDumpMdl->ByteOffset);
14108 
14109  ASSERT (NumberOfPages <= 16);
14110 
14111  PointerPte = MmCrashDumpPte;
14112  BaseVa = (PCHAR)MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte(PointerPte);
14113  MemoryDumpMdl->MappedSystemVa = (PCHAR)BaseVa + MemoryDumpMdl->ByteOffset;
14114  TempPte = ValidKernelPte;
14115  Page = (PPFN_NUMBER)(MemoryDumpMdl + 1);
14116 
14117  //
14118  // If the pages don't span the entire dump virtual address range,
14119  // build a barrier. Otherwise use the default barrier provided at the
14120  // end of the dump virtual address range.
14121  //
14122 
14123  if (NumberOfPages < 16) {
14124  MI_WRITE_ZERO_PTE (PointerPte + NumberOfPages);
14125  KiFlushSingleTb (BaseVa + (NumberOfPages << PAGE_SHIFT));
14126  }
14127 
14128  do {
14129 
14130 #pragma prefast(suppress: 2000, "SAL 1.2 needed for accurate MDL struct annotation.")
14131  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (*Page);
14132  TempPte = ValidKernelPte;
14133 
14134  switch (Pfn1->u3.e1.CacheAttribute) {
14135  case MiCached:
14136  break;
14137 
14138  case MiNonCached:
14139  MI_DISABLE_CACHING (TempPte);
14140  break;
14141 
14142  case MiWriteCombined:
14143  MI_SET_PTE_WRITE_COMBINE (TempPte);
14144  break;
14145 
14146  default:
14147  break;
14148  }
14149 
14150  TempPte.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber = *Page;
14151 
14152  //
14153  // Note this PTE may be valid or invalid prior to the overwriting here.
14154  //
14155 
14156  if (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 1) {
14157  if (PointerPte->u.Long != TempPte.u.Long) {
14158  MI_WRITE_VALID_PTE_NEW_PAGE (PointerPte, TempPte);
14159  KiFlushSingleTb (BaseVa);
14160  }
14161  }
14162  else {
14163  MI_WRITE_VALID_PTE (PointerPte, TempPte);
14164  }
14165 
14166  Page += 1;
14167  PointerPte += 1;
14168  BaseVa += PAGE_SIZE;
14169  NumberOfPages -= 1;
14170  } while (NumberOfPages != 0);
14171 
14172  return;
14173 }
14174 
14175 
14176 VOID
14177 MmReleaseDumpAddresses (
14178  IN PFN_NUMBER NumberOfPages
14179  )
14180 
14181 /*++
14182 
14183 Routine Description:
14184 
14185  For use by hibernate routine ONLY. Puts zeros back into the
14186  used dump PTEs.
14187 
14188 Arguments:
14189 
14190  NumberOfPages - Supplies the number of PTEs to zero.
14191 
14192 Return Value:
14193 
14194  None.
14195 
14196 --*/
14197 
14198 {
14199  PVOID BaseVa;
14200  PMMPTE PointerPte;
14201 
14202  PointerPte = MmCrashDumpPte;
14203  BaseVa = MiGetVirtualAddressMappedByPte (PointerPte);
14204 
14205  MiZeroMemoryPte (MmCrashDumpPte, NumberOfPages);
14206 
14207  while (NumberOfPages != 0) {
14208 
14209  KiFlushSingleTb (BaseVa);
14210 
14211  BaseVa = (PVOID) ((PCHAR) BaseVa + PAGE_SIZE);
14212  NumberOfPages -= 1;
14213  }
14214 }
14215 
14216 
14217 NTSTATUS
14218 MmSetBankedSection (
14219  __in HANDLE ProcessHandle,
14220  __in_bcount(BankLength) PVOID VirtualAddress,
14221  __in ULONG BankLength,
14222  __in BOOLEAN ReadWriteBank,
14223  __in PBANKED_SECTION_ROUTINE BankRoutine,
14224  __in PVOID Context
14225  )
14226 
14227 /*++
14228 
14229 Routine Description:
14230 
14231  This function declares a mapped video buffer as a banked
14232  section. This allows banked video devices (i.e., even
14233  though the video controller has a megabyte or so of memory,
14234  only a small bank (like 64k) can be mapped at any one time.
14235 
14236  In order to overcome this problem, the pager handles faults
14237  to this memory, unmaps the current bank, calls off to the
14238  video driver and then maps in the new bank.
14239 
14240  This function creates the necessary structures to allow the
14241  video driver to be called from the pager.
14242 
14243  ********************* NOTE NOTE NOTE *************************
14244  At this time only read/write banks are supported!
14245 
14246 Arguments:
14247 
14248  ProcessHandle - Supplies a handle to the process in which to
14249  support the banked video function.
14250 
14251  VirtualAddress - Supplies the virtual address where the video
14252  buffer is mapped in the specified process.
14253 
14254  BankLength - Supplies the size of the bank.
14255 
14256  ReadWriteBank - Supplies TRUE if the bank is read and write.
14257 
14258  BankRoutine - Supplies a pointer to the routine that should be
14259  called by the pager.
14260 
14261  Context - Supplies a context to be passed by the pager to the BankRoutine.
14262 
14263 Return Value:
14264 
14265  Returns the status of the function.
14266 
14267 Environment:
14268 
14269  Kernel mode, APC_LEVEL or below.
14270 
14271 --*/
14272 
14273 {
14274  KAPC_STATE ApcState;
14275  NTSTATUS Status;
14276  PETHREAD Thread;
14277  PEPROCESS Process;
14278  PMMVAD Vad;
14279  PMMPTE PointerPte;
14280  PMMPTE LastPte;
14281  MMPTE TempPte;
14282  ULONG_PTR size;
14283  ULONG count;
14284  ULONG NumberOfPtes;
14285  PMMBANKED_SECTION Bank;
14286 
14287  PAGED_CODE ();
14288 
14289  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (ReadWriteBank);
14290 
14291  //
14292  // Reference the specified process handle for VM_OPERATION access.
14293  //
14294 
14295  Status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle (ProcessHandle,
14296  PROCESS_VM_OPERATION,
14297  PsProcessType,
14298  KernelMode,
14299  (PVOID *)&Process,
14300  NULL);
14301 
14302  if (!NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
14303  return Status;
14304  }
14305 
14306  Thread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
14307 
14308  KeStackAttachProcess (&Process->Pcb, &ApcState);
14309 
14310  //
14311  // Get the address creation mutex to block multiple threads from
14312  // creating or deleting address space at the same time and
14313  // get the working set mutex so virtual address descriptors can
14314  // be inserted and walked. Block APCs so an APC which takes a page
14315  // fault does not corrupt various structures.
14316  //
14317 
14318  LOCK_ADDRESS_SPACE (Process);
14319 
14320  //
14321  // Make sure the address space was not deleted, if so, return an error.
14322  //
14323 
14324  if (Process->Flags & PS_PROCESS_FLAGS_VM_DELETED) {
14325  Status = STATUS_PROCESS_IS_TERMINATING;
14326  goto ErrorReturn;
14327  }
14328 
14329  Vad = MiLocateAddress (VirtualAddress);
14330 
14331  if ((Vad == NULL) ||
14332  (Vad->StartingVpn != MI_VA_TO_VPN (VirtualAddress)) ||
14333  (Vad->u.VadFlags.VadType != VadDevicePhysicalMemory)) {
14334  Status = STATUS_NOT_MAPPED_DATA;
14335  goto ErrorReturn;
14336  }
14337 
14338  size = PAGE_SIZE + ((Vad->EndingVpn - Vad->StartingVpn) << PAGE_SHIFT);
14339  if ((size % BankLength) != 0) {
14340  Status = STATUS_INVALID_VIEW_SIZE;
14341  goto ErrorReturn;
14342  }
14343 
14344  count = (ULONG) -1;
14345  NumberOfPtes = BankLength;
14346 
14347  do {
14348  NumberOfPtes >>= 1;
14349  count += 1;
14350  } while (NumberOfPtes != 0);
14351 
14352  //
14353  // Turn VAD into a banked VAD.
14354  //
14355 
14356  NumberOfPtes = BankLength >> PAGE_SHIFT;
14357 
14358  Bank = ExAllocatePoolWithTag (NonPagedPool,
14359  sizeof (MMBANKED_SECTION) +
14360  (NumberOfPtes - 1) * sizeof(MMPTE),
14361  'kBmM');
14362 
14363  if (Bank == NULL) {
14364  Status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
14365  goto ErrorReturn;
14366  }
14367 
14368  Bank->BankShift = PTE_SHIFT + count - PAGE_SHIFT;
14369 
14370  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (MI_VPN_TO_VA (Vad->StartingVpn));
14371  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 1);
14372 
14373  Bank->BasePhysicalPage = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (PointerPte);
14374  Bank->BasedPte = PointerPte;
14375  Bank->BankSize = BankLength;
14376  Bank->BankedRoutine = BankRoutine;
14377  Bank->Context = Context;
14378  Bank->CurrentMappedPte = PointerPte;
14379 
14380  //
14381  // Build the template PTEs structure.
14382  //
14383 
14384  MI_MAKE_VALID_USER_PTE (TempPte,
14385  Bank->BasePhysicalPage,
14386  MM_READWRITE,
14387  PointerPte);
14388 
14389  if (TempPte.u.Hard.Write) {
14390  MI_SET_PTE_DIRTY (TempPte);
14391  }
14392 
14393  count = 0;
14394 
14395  do {
14396  Bank->BankTemplate[count] = TempPte;
14397  TempPte.u.Hard.PageFrameNumber += 1;
14398  count += 1;
14399  } while (count < NumberOfPtes);
14400 
14401  LastPte = MiGetPteAddress (MI_VPN_TO_VA (Vad->EndingVpn));
14402 
14403  //
14404  // Set all PTEs within this range to zero. Any faults within
14405  // this range will call the banked routine before making the
14406  // page valid.
14407  //
14408 
14409  LOCK_WS_UNSAFE (Thread, Process);
14410 
14411  ((PMMVAD_LONG) Vad)->u4.Banked = Bank;
14412 
14413  MiZeroMemoryPte (PointerPte, size >> PAGE_SHIFT);
14414 
14415  MI_FLUSH_PROCESS_TB (FALSE);
14416 
14417  UNLOCK_WS_UNSAFE (Thread, Process);
14418 
14419  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
14420 
14421 ErrorReturn:
14422 
14423  UNLOCK_ADDRESS_SPACE (Process);
14424  KeUnstackDetachProcess (&ApcState);
14425  ObDereferenceObject (Process);
14426  return Status;
14427 }

14429 __out_bcount(NumberOfBytes) PVOID

14509 VOID
14510 MmLockPagedPool (
14511  IN PVOID Address,
14512  IN SIZE_T SizeInBytes
14513  )
14514 
14515 /*++
14516 
14517 Routine Description:
14518 
14519  Locks the specified address (which MUST reside in paged pool) into
14520  memory until MmUnlockPagedPool is called.
14521 
14522 Arguments:
14523 
14524  Address - Supplies the address in paged pool to lock.
14525 
14526  SizeInBytes - Supplies the size in bytes to lock.
14527 
14528 Return Value:
14529 
14530  None.
14531 
14532 Environment:
14533 
14534  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
14535 
14536 --*/
14537 
14538 {
14539  PMMPTE PointerPte;
14540  PMMPTE LastPte;
14541 
14542  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (Address);
14543  LastPte = MiGetPteAddress ((PVOID)((PCHAR)Address + (SizeInBytes - 1)));
14544 
14545  MiLockCode (PointerPte, LastPte, MM_LOCK_BY_REFCOUNT);
14546 
14547  return;
14548 }
14549 
14550 NTKERNELAPI
14551 VOID
14552 MmUnlockPagedPool (
14553  IN PVOID Address,
14554  IN SIZE_T SizeInBytes
14555  )
14556 
14557 /*++
14558 
14559 Routine Description:
14560 
14561  Unlocks paged pool that was locked with MmLockPagedPool.
14562 
14563 Arguments:
14564 
14565  Address - Supplies the address in paged pool to unlock.
14566 
14567  Size - Supplies the size to unlock.
14568 
14569 Return Value:
14570 
14571  None.
14572 
14573 Environment:
14574 
14575  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
14576 
14577 --*/
14578 
14579 {
14580  PMMPTE PointerPte;
14581  PMMPTE LastPte;
14582  KIRQL OldIrql;
14583  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
14584  PMMPFN Pfn1;
14585 
14586  PointerPte = MiGetPteAddress (Address);
14587  LastPte = MiGetPteAddress ((PVOID)((PCHAR)Address + (SizeInBytes - 1)));
14588 
14589  MmLockPageableSectionByHandle (ExPageLockHandle);
14590 
14591  LOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
14592 
14593  do {
14594  ASSERT (PointerPte->u.Hard.Valid == 1);
14595 
14596  PageFrameIndex = MI_GET_PAGE_FRAME_FROM_PTE (PointerPte);
14597  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
14598 
14599  ASSERT (Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount > 1);
14600 
14601  MI_REMOVE_LOCKED_PAGE_CHARGE_AND_DECREF (Pfn1);
14602 
14603  PointerPte += 1;
14604  } while (PointerPte <= LastPte);
14605 
14606  UNLOCK_PFN (OldIrql);
14607  MmUnlockPageableImageSection (ExPageLockHandle);
14608  return;
14609 }
14610 
14611 NTKERNELAPI
14612 ULONG
14613 MmGatherMemoryForHibernate (
14614  IN PMDL Mdl,
14615  IN BOOLEAN Wait
14616  )
14617 
14618 /*++
14619 
14620 Routine Description:
14621 
14622  Finds enough memory to fill in the pages of the MDL for power management
14623  hibernate function.
14624 
14625 Arguments:
14626 
14627  Mdl - Supplies an MDL, the start VA field should be NULL. The length
14628  field indicates how many pages to obtain.
14629 
14630  Wait - FALSE to fail immediately if the pages aren't available.
14631 
14632 Return Value:
14633 
14634  TRUE if the MDL could be filled in, FALSE otherwise.
14635 
14636 Environment:
14637 
14638  Kernel mode, IRQL of DISPATCH_LEVEL or below.
14639 
14640 --*/
14641 
14642 {
14643  PMMPFNLIST ListHead;
14644  KIRQL OldIrql;
14645  PFN_NUMBER AvailablePages;
14646  PFN_NUMBER PagesNeeded;
14647  PPFN_NUMBER Pages;
14648  PFN_NUMBER i;
14649  PFN_NUMBER PageFrameIndex;
14650  PMMPFN Pfn1;
14651  ULONG status;
14652  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
14653 
14654  status = FALSE;
14655 
14656  PagesNeeded = Mdl->ByteCount >> PAGE_SHIFT;
14657  Pages = (PPFN_NUMBER)(Mdl + 1);
14658 
14659  i = Wait ? 100 : 1;
14660 
14661  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
14662 
14663  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
14664 
14665  InterlockedIncrement (&MiDelayPageFaults);
14666 
14667  do {
14668 
14669  LOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
14670 
14671  MiDeferredUnlockPages (MI_DEFER_PFN_HELD);
14672 
14673  //
14674  // Don't use MmAvailablePages here because if compression hardware is
14675  // being used we would bail prematurely. Check the lists explicitly
14676  // in order to provide our caller with the maximum number of pages.
14677  //
14678 
14679  AvailablePages = MmZeroedPageListHead.Total + MmFreePageListHead.Total;
14680 
14681  for (ListHead = &MmStandbyPageListByPriority[0];
14682  ListHead < &MmStandbyPageListByPriority[MI_PFN_PRIORITIES];
14683  ListHead += 1) {
14684 
14685  AvailablePages += ListHead->Total;
14686  }
14687 
14688  if (AvailablePages > PagesNeeded) {
14689 
14690  //
14691  // Fill in the MDL.
14692  //
14693 
14694  do {
14695  PageFrameIndex = MiRemoveAnyPage (MI_GET_PAGE_COLOR_FROM_PTE (NULL));
14696  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (PageFrameIndex);
14697 #if DBG
14698  Pfn1->PteAddress = (PVOID) (ULONG_PTR)X64K;
14699 #endif
14700  MI_SET_PFN_DELETED (Pfn1);
14701  Pfn1->u3.e2.ReferenceCount += 1;
14702  Pfn1->OriginalPte.u.Long = MM_DEMAND_ZERO_WRITE_PTE;
14703  *Pages = PageFrameIndex;
14704  Pages += 1;
14705  PagesNeeded -= 1;
14706  } while (PagesNeeded);
14707  UNLOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
14708  Mdl->MdlFlags |= MDL_PAGES_LOCKED;
14709  status = TRUE;
14710  break;
14711  }
14712 
14713  UNLOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
14714 
14715  //
14716  // If we're being called at DISPATCH_LEVEL we cannot move pages to
14717  // the standby list because mutexes must be acquired to do so.
14718  //
14719 
14720  if (OldIrql > APC_LEVEL) {
14721  break;
14722  }
14723 
14724  if (!i) {
14725  break;
14726  }
14727 
14728  //
14729  // Attempt to move pages to the standby list.
14730  //
14731 
14732  MmEmptyAllWorkingSets ();
14733  MiFlushAllPages();
14734 
14735  KeDelayExecutionThread (KernelMode,
14736  FALSE,
14737  (PLARGE_INTEGER)&Mm30Milliseconds);
14738  i -= 1;
14739 
14740  } while (TRUE);
14741 
14742  InterlockedDecrement (&MiDelayPageFaults);
14743 
14744  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread (CurrentThread);
14745 
14746  return status;
14747 }
14748 
14749 NTKERNELAPI
14750 VOID
14751 MmReturnMemoryForHibernate (
14752  IN PMDL Mdl
14753  )
14754 
14755 /*++
14756 
14757 Routine Description:
14758 
14759  Returns memory from MmGatherMemoryForHibername.
14760 
14761 Arguments:
14762 
14763  Mdl - Supplies an MDL, the start VA field should be NULL. The length
14764  field indicates how many pages to obtain.
14765 
14766 Return Value:
14767 
14768  None.
14769 
14770 Environment:
14771 
14772  Kernel mode, IRQL of APC_LEVEL or below.
14773 
14774 --*/
14775 
14776 {
14777  PMMPFN Pfn1;
14778  KIRQL OldIrql;
14779  PPFN_NUMBER Pages;
14780  PPFN_NUMBER LastPage;
14781 
14782  Pages = (PPFN_NUMBER)(Mdl + 1);
14783  LastPage = Pages + (Mdl->ByteCount >> PAGE_SHIFT);
14784 
14785  LOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
14786 
14787  do {
14788  Pfn1 = MI_PFN_ELEMENT (*Pages);
14789  MiDecrementReferenceCount (Pfn1, *Pages);
14790  Pages += 1;
14791  } while (Pages < LastPage);
14792 
14793  UNLOCK_PFN2 (OldIrql);
14794  return;
14795 }
